00:21:02.640 --> 00:21:08.720
[Amit Varma]: coming to a respect for tradition not as a respect for tradition per se on its own but simply a

00:21:08.720 --> 00:21:13.280
[Amit Varma]: respect for the processes that make tradition what it is and therefore understanding that is

00:21:13.280 --> 00:21:20.000
[Amit Varma]: harder to break that down. Whereas the question I would ask is and again I am much less knowledgeable

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:28.400
[Amit Varma]: than you about this like I haven't I'm also not an expert on it. I could easily be wrong but then

00:21:28.400 --> 00:21:34.560
[Amit Varma]: my question is my question slash speculation is that for example the book you referred to by

00:21:34.560 --> 00:21:41.600
[Amit Varma]: Chhibber and Rahul Varma is called ideology and identity and my question then is that how much

00:21:41.600 --> 00:21:46.160
[Amit Varma]: can we how much does one arise from the other how much does the former arise from the latter

00:21:46.160 --> 00:21:51.280
[Amit Varma]: how much does ideology arise from identity in the sense as you yourself made the point that okay

00:21:51.280 --> 00:21:56.240
[Amit Varma]: there are social contexts in which ideologies emerge now one can look back at some of these

00:21:56.240 --> 00:22:00.160
[Amit Varma]: thinkers like the book you mentioned from the Gita Press which again I haven't read so I don't

00:22:00.160 --> 00:22:05.440
[Amit Varma]: want to impute something but where for example one might say that okay they might be expressing

00:22:05.440 --> 00:22:10.800
[Amit Varma]: conservative thoughts in terms of respecting tradition that someone like Burke may agree with

00:22:10.800 --> 00:22:15.600
[Amit Varma]: but the source of that expression is say they want to preserve the caste system for example.

00:22:16.160 --> 00:22:21.920
[Guest]: So yeah so this is a what Paul Ricoeur calls hermetics of suspicion that we should look at

00:22:21.920 --> 00:22:27.120
[Guest]: these treatises and ideologies as to presume suspicion what are they trying to preserve what

00:22:27.120 --> 00:22:31.280
[Guest]: is their hidden intent they may themselves may not be aware what they are trying to do you know

00:22:31.280 --> 00:22:38.160
[Guest]: when they put forth certain ideas but let me kind of so it is very difficult to actually settle this

00:22:38.160 --> 00:22:44.480
[Guest]: question because intents are not so easily kind of deciphered from even reading or even seeing the

00:22:44.480 --> 00:22:48.160
[Guest]: behavior of a person so clearly because we do not have that level of knowledge.

00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:52.160
[Guest]: In fact a person himself may not realize. May not realize because they are yeah I mean

00:22:52.160 --> 00:22:56.240
[Guest]: you have to be careful about what they realize and how they construct their kind of ideas.

00:22:56.240 --> 00:23:00.400
[Guest]: So just to take the example of again Garpatri Maharaj his critique is significantly critique

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:07.840
[Guest]: of materialism and the ability of human thought to understand social forces and modify them through

00:23:08.320 --> 00:23:14.000
[Guest]: you know the means of the state and I mean politically powerful state. So there is an

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:18.400
[Guest]: intellectual critique there. It is so that intellectual critique may be motivated by an

00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:23.840
[Guest]: intent to preserve a social order which did have even at that time even today has quite a bit of

00:23:23.840 --> 00:23:28.640
[Amit Varma]: injustice built into it. It could be and it may not be. So what you are saying is ignore what the

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:33.120
[Guest]: intent might be and just focus on the intellectual content. I don't think we should ignore it.

00:23:33.120 --> 00:23:40.080
[Guest]: I think any tradition should certainly try to incorporate the suspicion into it because there

00:23:40.080 --> 00:23:46.880
[Guest]: is in especially in our traditions I do think that there is a lot of I mean practices which

00:23:46.880 --> 00:23:51.760
[Guest]: are preserved in the name of just preserving the tradition. So if somebody is looking at it from a

00:23:51.760 --> 00:23:57.360
[Guest]: suspicious perspective bringing a hermetic of suspicion and saying that hey this particular

00:23:57.360 --> 00:24:01.680
[Guest]: practice is just trying to preserve certain kind of privileges and all of that. We should try to

00:24:01.680 --> 00:24:07.920
[Guest]: be fair to that perspective because this suspicion might make us better over time.

00:24:07.920 --> 00:24:13.440
[Guest]: We should try to deal with it in our own kind of ways and we should debate it, talk about it.

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:18.240
[Guest]: What you should not do is reject it upfront because it is true that many people who think

00:24:18.240 --> 00:24:22.800
[Guest]: of the word in a suspicious manner are sometimes wrong and sometimes half right

00:24:22.800 --> 00:24:26.320
[Guest]: but they are also quite often right and they do have a point often.

00:24:26.320 --> 00:24:32.560
[Amit Varma]: So is it fair to say that as far as the discourse is concerned it's better to focus on the effect

00:24:32.560 --> 00:24:40.400
[Amit Varma]: rather than the intent. For example if something that you are talking about also has the effect of

00:24:40.400 --> 00:24:44.880
[Amit Varma]: say preserving some privileges like the caste system just to use one example. Would it be

00:24:44.880 --> 00:24:49.520
[Amit Varma]: better to focus on that instead of turning attention on the person and say oh he is saying

00:24:49.520 --> 00:24:56.080
[Amit Varma]: it because he wants xyz to continue because I think that poisons a lot of the discourse when

00:24:56.080 --> 00:25:02.240
[Amit Varma]: the focus turns to the intent of the person rather than arguing on the basis of the argument itself.

00:25:02.240 --> 00:25:07.120
[Guest]: So what do you mean by intent? So yeah I think it's not particularly useful if you get personal

00:25:07.120 --> 00:25:12.240
[Guest]: and say Karpatri Maharaj was making an argument to preserve this, Raja Gopalacharya was arguing

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:18.400
[Guest]: for a certain kind of education system which put the kid in the household's vocation for half a day

00:25:18.400 --> 00:25:22.880
[Guest]: because they were trying to preserve the caste system and all that. So the individual kind of

00:25:22.880 --> 00:25:29.280
[Guest]: attribution of intent is I think a little tricky because it makes the conversation very difficult.

00:25:29.280 --> 00:25:34.160
[Guest]: But we do have to recognize the structural forces that may be at work. I use that term

00:25:34.160 --> 00:25:40.480
[Guest]: with a great deal of hesitation because I think structural analysis is often overrated and it

00:25:41.280 --> 00:25:45.840
[Guest]: pretends to have more insight than it really does. But I think there is something to that.

00:25:45.840 --> 00:25:50.160
[Guest]: So now if you were to kind of broaden that discussion and let's look back at the assaults

00:25:50.160 --> 00:25:56.000
[Guest]: that were made on religion and the most powerful assaults that have been made in other traditions,

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:00.320
[Guest]: in the Western tradition specifically, the assault by Marx, assault by Nietzsche,

00:26:00.320 --> 00:26:06.320
[Guest]: assault by Freud for example. You read this, in fact this hermeneutics of suspicion term comes

00:26:06.320 --> 00:26:11.280
[Guest]: from their treatment of, so Marx made it about class interest. This is trying to preserve

00:26:11.280 --> 00:26:14.960
[Guest]: certain kind of class interest. There is a much more interesting critique of ideology and

00:26:15.520 --> 00:26:24.000
[Guest]: this religion that he makes. Then Freud makes it about much more of the subconscious forces and

00:26:24.000 --> 00:26:29.760
[Guest]: the psychological explanations for it. Nietzsche has a much different explanation of,

00:26:29.760 --> 00:26:34.400
[Guest]: a genealogical explanation for it. And all of these, if you were to think carefully and try

00:26:34.400 --> 00:26:39.760
[Guest]: to incorporate, they might reveal some truths about society. So I would say just take the idea,

00:26:41.200 --> 00:26:45.920
[Guest]: not just the consequence of the idea, but also the idea in itself and see what's in it.

00:26:46.720 --> 00:26:50.720
[Guest]: Because I think the consequences are where people have disagreements on, a lot of disagreements on

00:26:50.720 --> 00:26:54.640
[Guest]: what is the good society, what is the good state of the world. So you say that, look at the

00:26:54.640 --> 00:26:57.600
[Guest]: consequence, but it's not so simple to look at the consequence because there are no agreements

00:26:57.600 --> 00:27:01.680
[Guest]: on the consequence. The whole point of disagreement is that we disagree on what a good society

00:27:02.240 --> 00:27:06.320
[Amit Varma]: might look like. And some people might privilege group rights, some people might privilege

00:27:06.320 --> 00:27:12.080
[Guest]: individual rights. And some may say that certain kind of privileges are justified. For example,

00:27:12.080 --> 00:27:15.680
[Guest]: many libertarians say that if you are a multi-billionaire, you have worked, built a

00:27:15.680 --> 00:27:19.120
[Guest]: business or even if you inherited, it's your business and you should enjoy that privilege.

00:27:19.120 --> 00:27:24.560
[Guest]: Some people say that income inequality is obscene and unfair and it is disproportionate and based on

00:27:24.560 --> 00:27:28.880
[Guest]: past privileges and all. They may have a point there also. But the point is that these are

00:27:28.880 --> 00:27:32.960
[Guest]: points of substantive moral disagreements. That is where the division will happen. So it's not so

00:27:32.960 --> 00:27:36.640
[Guest]: simple that you look at the consequence and you will settle the debate. I don't think for example,

00:27:36.640 --> 00:27:40.960
[Guest]: earlier you said that if a libertarian wants to have an argument with somebody who is interested

00:27:40.960 --> 00:27:45.760
[Guest]: in equality, then if you can show that equality will be achieved through libertarian means.

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:51.520
[Guest]: I think it's a little naive to say that there is a such easy reconcilability of these points of view.

00:27:51.520 --> 00:27:55.440
[Guest]: These points of view are fundamentally irreconcilable. Rawls and Nozick are not,

00:27:56.080 --> 00:28:00.240
[Guest]: can't be reconciled. So simply, if you were to just talk about 20th century thought,

00:28:00.240 --> 00:28:03.440
[Guest]: because their points of departure, what is good is very different.

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:06.640
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's not just then a question of what your first principles are, whether it's,

00:28:06.640 --> 00:28:10.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, freedom on one side or equality on the other side. The difference also lies in

00:28:10.800 --> 00:28:16.640
[Amit Varma]: how differently you look at consequences. And therefore, you can't reconcile them from either.

00:28:16.640 --> 00:28:22.160
[Guest]: It's not so simple to reconcile. But I think the interesting thing is to keep having this

00:28:22.160 --> 00:28:26.880
[Guest]: conversation. So I agree with you on this point, find ways to have conversations, right? Like,

00:28:26.880 --> 00:28:30.480
[Guest]: what we have seen in the last four or five years, and especially even going back earlier,

00:28:30.480 --> 00:28:34.720
[Guest]: I don't want to say only four or five years, is the framing of political differences in

00:28:34.720 --> 00:28:39.600
[Guest]: very Schmittian terms, you know, Carl Schmitt wrote this book called concept of the political,

00:28:39.600 --> 00:28:44.400
[Guest]: where he framed political differences as, you know, friends and enemies. So political

00:28:44.400 --> 00:28:49.280
[Guest]: opponents are your enemies. And the supremely political moment is when you realize somebody

00:28:49.280 --> 00:28:54.800
[Guest]: is an enemy. So that's his idea of the political. And more and more we are seeing framing of the

00:28:54.800 --> 00:29:00.720
[Guest]: political in this kind of a way, which I think is very inimical to this very binary way.

00:29:01.600 --> 00:29:06.880
[Guest]: It's binary, and it is not just binary, it's also, it has a phenomenal consequence for the way we

00:29:06.880 --> 00:29:11.280
[Guest]: kind of perceive the world around us. I mean, these are, I mean, very important differences,

00:29:11.280 --> 00:29:15.200
[Guest]: let's not underplay the importance of political differences, you know, like, you can't say that

00:29:15.200 --> 00:29:18.880
[Guest]: a Soviet Union person who supports the Soviet Union, a person who supports a very different

00:29:18.880 --> 00:29:24.000
[Guest]: system is in consequence, the difference is highly consequential, there is a lot at stake,

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:29.360
[Guest]: the stakes are very high. But how do we play this very high stakes, kind of, like, I don't

00:29:29.360 --> 00:29:34.560
[Guest]: know, use the word game, but how do we participate in this kind of high stakes contestation,

00:29:34.560 --> 00:29:40.640
[Guest]: without framing this as friends versus enemies kind of situation, because then if it's the enemy,

00:29:40.640 --> 00:29:46.000
[Guest]: then all means are fair. And then I mean, you can't have institutions preserved, you can't have

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:51.040
[Guest]: many other, you know, things that are required at the foundation to have political conversation.

00:29:51.040 --> 00:29:54.640
[Guest]: And unfortunately, in the last few years in India, we are seeing a lot of this framing,

00:29:54.640 --> 00:30:00.160
[Guest]: which is so extreme, that it is and on all sides, I would say, I mean, I don't want to say a little

00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:04.960
[Guest]: bit more perhaps on one side than the other. But framing is I think, if you were to I don't

00:30:04.960 --> 00:30:10.800
[Guest]: believe in having absolute kind of, you know, NT conditions to have a conversation, but

00:30:10.800 --> 00:30:14.240
[Guest]: commitment to at least having a conversation is the entry point to have that conversation,

00:30:14.240 --> 00:30:18.080
[Guest]: right? Because otherwise, you get into this paradox of intolerance and so on so forth.

00:30:18.080 --> 00:30:22.640
[Amit Varma]: No, and I'm totally thinking of Twitter right now, given all that you've said and Twitter,

00:30:22.640 --> 00:30:27.440
[Amit Varma]: I would say is now that I've learned a new phrase from you is a very Schmittian environment.

00:30:27.440 --> 00:30:33.600
[Guest]: I think Twitter brings out every person is better in real life than on Twitter. And

00:30:34.720 --> 00:30:39.760
[Guest]: they are better on Facebook than on Twitter. They are better in a blog than on Facebook.

00:30:39.760 --> 00:30:45.280
[Guest]: And so the formats do have a kind of constraint that they present and especially the conversation

00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:50.720
[Guest]: is political. And the I mean, differences are highly emotional. And it's also the nature of

00:30:50.720 --> 00:30:55.520
[Guest]: the way we kind of form political opinion, how we take sides, a lot of it is emotional,

00:30:55.520 --> 00:30:59.360
[Amit Varma]: and there are passions involved. And also Cass Sunstein referred to this phenomenon called

00:30:59.360 --> 00:31:04.160
[Amit Varma]: group polarization. And what you see a lot on Twitter is not only do you quickly get divided

00:31:04.720 --> 00:31:09.600
[Amit Varma]: along these quote unquote, tribal lines, in terms of friends and enemies like to use that

00:31:09.600 --> 00:31:14.160
[Amit Varma]: Schmittian phrase, I'm going to keep saying Schmittian. But, but what also happens is that

00:31:14.160 --> 00:31:19.280
[Amit Varma]: then most political discourse on Twitter just simply becomes a way of raising your status

00:31:19.280 --> 00:31:25.440
[Amit Varma]: within your own in group by signaling how strongly you feel and therefore the discourse gets more

00:31:25.440 --> 00:31:31.360
[Amit Varma]: and more polarized. And the bizarre thing is, you know, like what I keep ranting about is that

00:31:31.360 --> 00:31:36.400
[Amit Varma]: people think in binaries, you know, like I have been called both the Congress even have criticized

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:41.680
[Amit Varma]: Modi or Sanghi amazingly enough, and I've criticized Rahul Gandhi. And the thing is,

00:31:41.680 --> 00:31:45.440
[Amit Varma]: you can't really converse like that. Because of course, I've criticized them both. And of course,

00:31:45.440 --> 00:31:49.360
[Amit Varma]: I've criticized Modi much more because he happens to hold the reins of government.

00:31:49.360 --> 00:31:54.720
[Amit Varma]: So you're always trying to speak truth to power. But the point is that, you know, once you form

00:31:54.720 --> 00:31:59.680
[Amit Varma]: these binary sort of tribal camps, then the political discussion is useless. It's all

00:31:59.680 --> 00:32:05.520
[Guest]: signaling and you're not actually discussing issues. Yeah, so the root of this is that people

00:32:05.520 --> 00:32:10.160
[Guest]: are coming from very different premises. The ideological premises are very different. And

00:32:10.800 --> 00:32:16.320
[Guest]: people who share those premises for them. This is a no brainer, like you can 140 characters,

00:32:16.320 --> 00:32:20.640
[Guest]: not even to 80, 140 characters, say something that will just make sense to them, of course,

00:32:20.640 --> 00:32:26.400
[Guest]: but people who don't share those premises will be aghast that something like that can be said,

00:32:26.400 --> 00:32:32.240
[Guest]: you know. So, for example, if you see on Twitter, a libertarian says tax is theft.

00:32:33.120 --> 00:32:37.040
[Guest]: Libertarians say that there's a genuine kind of, this is a line that they use.

00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:41.040
[Guest]: – Taxation is theft. – Taxation is theft, they say. Then

00:32:41.040 --> 00:32:46.960
[Guest]: and somebody else who is, thinks of morality and political ideology differently, and says things

00:32:46.960 --> 00:32:51.440
[Guest]: that taxation is important to not just for the public goods, also for redistribution and all,

00:32:51.440 --> 00:32:56.880
[Guest]: will be aghast at that and they'll see this as a provocation, right. Now, the libertarian didn't

00:32:56.880 --> 00:33:01.600
[Guest]: mean it as a provocation, because it's just so central to their worldview, that taxation is

00:33:01.600 --> 00:33:07.840
[Guest]: theft, you know, it's something that is canonical to their worldview. And somebody else thinks very

00:33:07.840 --> 00:33:13.280
[Guest]: differently about it. So, that's why I think the way the political ideologies in modern world are

00:33:13.280 --> 00:33:19.120
[Guest]: kind of taking shape, there is a great deal of difference on basic premises about what it is and

00:33:19.120 --> 00:33:23.280
[Guest]: that in communications. So, when we go and participate in the public sphere, it makes

00:33:23.280 --> 00:33:26.960
[Guest]: communication much more difficult because our premises are different. This is a point on which

00:33:26.960 --> 00:33:32.000
[Guest]: Alasdair MacIntyre is very good. He kind of, he has in his two books, who's just his wish

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:37.120
[Guest]: rationality and after virtue, kind of tried in the, at least in the Western context, find out

00:33:37.120 --> 00:33:41.680
[Guest]: the roots of the kind of differences. Although we also have some of these similar kind of debates,

00:33:41.680 --> 00:33:44.960
[Guest]: and we do have a certain globalization of discourse that is happening over time. So,

00:33:44.960 --> 00:33:48.880
[Guest]: we can also see the kind of underlying differences, there's a lot to learn from

00:33:48.880 --> 00:33:55.120
[Guest]: this kind of analysis. But the irreconcilability is one part. But the second part is also,

00:33:55.120 --> 00:33:59.920
[Guest]: which he says is that the person who makes the argument makes it as if it's a no brainer.

00:33:59.920 --> 00:34:03.840
[Guest]: Like a person who says, of course, it's a fundamental right to privacy. There's ways

00:34:03.840 --> 00:34:08.160
[Guest]: that could debate about that, right. And another person will say that, hey, I may have a different

00:34:08.160 --> 00:34:13.360
[Guest]: view about that. And this is a very common thing that happens in our discussions and much more on

00:34:13.360 --> 00:34:18.640
[Guest]: Twitter, because Twitter is like that. It's just reaction quickly, that how can you have a debate

00:34:18.640 --> 00:34:24.000
[Guest]: on that? Of course, I can have a debate on that. So, it's really it goes back to the foundation

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:28.480
[Guest]: of these ideas. And then of course, emotions get involved. And emotions shape ideas, ideas

00:34:28.480 --> 00:34:33.600
[Guest]: shape emotions, that's an endless kind of discussion we can have. But there is...

00:34:33.600 --> 00:34:38.560
[Amit Varma]: It gets mitty in very fast. You know, you just picked that taxation is theft example,

00:34:38.560 --> 00:34:42.160
[Amit Varma]: because I'm sitting across you, but I should point out is very unfair, because there are like

00:34:42.160 --> 00:34:47.280
[Amit Varma]: two and a half libertarians in all of India. And as far as you the specific example is concerned,

00:34:47.280 --> 00:34:52.160
[Amit Varma]: taxation is theft. I think every sensible libertarian would say that taxation is theft,

00:34:52.160 --> 00:34:56.400
[Amit Varma]: but we need some theft. In the sense that look, how do you define theft? It's taking money by

00:34:56.400 --> 00:35:01.680
[Amit Varma]: force from someone. And the thing is, I think everyone can agree that no one would contribute

00:35:01.680 --> 00:35:06.000
[Amit Varma]: money to the government on their own if it was not illegal to not pay taxes. And therefore,

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:10.880
[Amit Varma]: by that definition, it is theft slash decoitry. And we would also argue that you need some because

00:35:10.880 --> 00:35:14.560
[Amit Varma]: you do need a state to protect your rights or whatever, whatever. But that's a completely

00:35:14.560 --> 00:35:18.480
[Amit Varma]: separate debate. We won't get into that now that we have established that taxation is indeed theft.

00:35:19.600 --> 00:35:23.200
[Amit Varma]: And that I'm fine with it. So kill me. I'll let you have a last word on it for now.

00:35:24.640 --> 00:35:26.880
[Guest]: But Indian Republic has had many, many last words.

00:35:26.880 --> 00:35:34.000
[Amit Varma]: So the other question is to sort of go back, I told you that there were a number of questions

00:35:34.000 --> 00:35:38.960
[Amit Varma]: raised by when you were speaking about the notion that there might be a conservative tradition in

00:35:38.960 --> 00:35:45.840
[Amit Varma]: India. And another sort of a question that I often for example, I've asked other guests like

00:35:45.840 --> 00:35:52.480
[Amit Varma]: Shashi Tharoor and so on, and got a variety of different answers. Shashi Tharoor, Akar Patel

00:35:52.480 --> 00:35:58.080
[Amit Varma]: and different people who've been on the show is that there is an argument often made, I think

00:35:58.080 --> 00:36:03.040
[Amit Varma]: Dindayal Upadhyay made a version of this argument, that the Indian Constitution being liberal,

00:36:03.040 --> 00:36:06.720
[Amit Varma]: though I feel it's not liberal enough in terms of protecting individual rights, but let's say

00:36:06.720 --> 00:36:12.160
[Amit Varma]: it's more liberal than Indian society, that the Indian Constitution being a liberal constitution,

00:36:12.160 --> 00:36:18.080
[Amit Varma]: if we granted that is actually be a liberal constitution imposed on an illiberal society

00:36:18.080 --> 00:36:23.280
[Amit Varma]: to use the language of the liberals, or on a conservative society to use different language.

00:36:23.280 --> 00:36:28.400
[Amit Varma]: And that imposition itself cannot be liberal. I mean, the conservative viewpoint, of course,

00:36:28.400 --> 00:36:34.640
[Amit Varma]: is that look, society has to change from within, that change cannot be forced from top.

00:36:34.640 --> 00:36:39.760
[Amit Varma]: And by and large, there is a lot of merit to that as far as the enforceability of change is

00:36:39.760 --> 00:36:44.640
[Amit Varma]: concerned, but not necessarily the morality of change. Because two questions that then come up

00:36:44.640 --> 00:36:50.880
[Amit Varma]: is one, how do you reconcile the imposition of a liberal constitution? Because if it is imposed,

00:36:50.880 --> 00:36:56.480
[Amit Varma]: how can it be liberal on a society which may not be as liberal as the constitution itself?

00:36:56.480 --> 00:37:00.800
[Amit Varma]: And two, what do you then do about things like say, Sati, Sati was outlawed. Now,

00:37:00.800 --> 00:37:05.600
[Amit Varma]: there could be people who would argue that look, we are a society which believes in group rights,

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:10.240
[Amit Varma]: this is a tradition. And why should we protect individual rights? Because just because some

00:37:10.240 --> 00:37:15.360
[Amit Varma]: liberal somewhere says that, and you know, to both of us, of course, it seems completely

00:37:15.360 --> 00:37:20.880
[Amit Varma]: obvious that Sati had to be outlawed. And yeah, it's, it's a given. But how do we then reconcile

00:37:20.880 --> 00:37:24.880
[Amit Varma]: that with the conservative belief that society can only change from within? And if there are

00:37:24.880 --> 00:37:29.360
[Amit Varma]: exceptions to that, how do we demarcate those exceptions? And how do we enforce them without

00:37:29.360 --> 00:37:34.320
[Guest]: that enforcing being illiberal? So, this is a very big and difficult question to answer.

00:37:34.320 --> 00:37:40.320
[Guest]: Because, I mean, there are 10,000 questions hidden there in that one question, but,

00:37:40.320 --> 00:37:45.520
[Guest]: and I don't want to answer it in a manner that I have some kind of a glib response to it, because

00:37:45.520 --> 00:37:51.600
[Guest]: it's not, it's not something which is can be settled based on some quick, some very simple

00:37:51.600 --> 00:37:56.960
[Guest]: principles, you know, it's not something very easy to settle because you do see when you say

00:37:56.960 --> 00:38:02.240
[Guest]: that society should reform on its own, you see certain practices that are very repugnant to

00:38:02.240 --> 00:38:08.640
[Guest]: most individuals and then you say, okay, why is this still kind of in place? And so, for example,

00:38:08.640 --> 00:38:13.920
[Guest]: taking a Sati example, there was some practice of Sati and when it was abolished, there is very

00:38:13.920 --> 00:38:20.080
[Guest]: little actual resistance from the society on that evolution, there was some degree of you would say,

00:38:20.080 --> 00:38:24.480
[Guest]: I would, I don't know enough, but I would argue there was some degree of acceptance by the society

00:38:24.480 --> 00:38:28.480
[Guest]: that there is a problem here. And when it was abolished at that point, if you see there was not

00:38:28.480 --> 00:38:33.840
[Guest]: that much resistance against that. So, sometimes you do need the state to do something which

00:38:33.840 --> 00:38:39.360
[Guest]: actually the society was almost on the verge or could have done it, but there was some reason

00:38:39.360 --> 00:38:45.520
[Guest]: social and I mean, institutional reason because of which it was not able to do it, its own internal

00:38:45.520 --> 00:38:49.840
[Guest]: checks and balances had broken down or it was not working well enough on that particular point.

00:38:49.840 --> 00:38:54.240
[Guest]: So, it's not so simple that either society should settle on its own, the state should settle,

00:38:54.240 --> 00:39:00.640
[Guest]: it's an issue that needs consideration, careful consideration about the situation that we find

00:39:00.640 --> 00:39:05.440
[Guest]: ourselves in and then what is the state can do and what the society can do. But what I do think

00:39:05.440 --> 00:39:13.360
[Guest]: is required in a constitutional republic that we kind of built in 1950 are some basic minimum

00:39:13.360 --> 00:39:19.440
[Guest]: standards, which are mostly in the form of rights that are protected by a constitutional state,

00:39:19.440 --> 00:39:25.760
[Guest]: which protects those rights in a manner that is predictable and it is based on rule of law,

00:39:26.320 --> 00:39:32.080
[Guest]: it does not discriminate, it does not do any kind of arbitrary action, those rights protect for

00:39:32.080 --> 00:39:37.840
[Guest]: everybody equally. That is, I think many people across political spectrum might agree with that.

00:39:38.800 --> 00:39:46.640
[Guest]: Where they may have a difference is on issues of religious reform using state power, issues of

00:39:46.640 --> 00:39:51.360
[Guest]: whether there should be a special recognition given to certain kind of groups, for example,

00:39:51.360 --> 00:39:56.400
[Guest]: you know. There is a, for example, reservation. Now, if suppose you did not have a reservation

00:39:56.400 --> 00:40:01.360
[Guest]: on day one of our kind of independence, you would have very, I mean, most of the senior

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:06.480
[Guest]: government positions filled with a few social groups. Can you have that and have legitimacy

00:40:07.520 --> 00:40:13.920
[Guest]: in the state? It is very difficult to say that you would, right, because I mean, you need to

00:40:13.920 --> 00:40:18.080
[Guest]: have legitimacy, you need to have legitimacy in the representation through the democratic system

00:40:18.080 --> 00:40:20.960
[Guest]: of elections and all that, but also in the administrative state, you need to have some

00:40:20.960 --> 00:40:25.920
[Guest]: degree of legitimacy. You cannot say that only a few, I mean, people who are, who had the education

00:40:25.920 --> 00:40:29.840
[Guest]: early on, who had that kind of advantage should certainly dominate the Indian state.

00:40:30.800 --> 00:40:36.560
[Guest]: So, in the Indian context, there are two issues that make this much more complicated. One is the

00:40:36.560 --> 00:40:42.880
[Guest]: issue of certain communities that have kind of historical disadvantages, especially the Dalits,

00:40:42.880 --> 00:40:48.320
[Guest]: for example, there have been a significant disadvantage when we got independence.

00:40:48.320 --> 00:40:54.320
[Guest]: And then the question of majority versus minority. So, this framing that there is a Hindu

00:40:54.320 --> 00:41:00.560
[Guest]: majority and there are other minorities and how do you ensure that there is some kind of

00:41:00.560 --> 00:41:06.080
[Guest]: majoritarianism does not go to the extent of, you know, destroying the rights of minorities and,

00:41:06.080 --> 00:41:11.840
[Guest]: you know, doing something which is more domination of sorts, you know. So, these issues kind of

00:41:11.840 --> 00:41:17.280
[Guest]: problematized this framing that you should have just simple equal rights for everybody and

00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:22.800
[Guest]: protected by the state. So, then you had to do more of, you know, recognition through reservations

00:41:22.800 --> 00:41:29.440
[Guest]: and other things. And you had to have a politics when you can argue that. So, I am arguing one side

00:41:29.440 --> 00:41:36.560
[Guest]: of it, where there is a recognition that you need to give a certain degree of comfort to speak

00:41:36.560 --> 00:41:42.560
[Guest]: politically to different groups who might otherwise feel like they are probably at the

00:41:42.560 --> 00:41:49.200
[Guest]: risk of being marginalized. In that, the main instrument through which this can be done is

00:41:49.200 --> 00:41:57.200
[Guest]: state power. So, state power is required to do these things. And the question that I have and

00:41:57.200 --> 00:42:03.200
[Guest]: I think it requires more thinking and more walking around is that how do we ensure that this happens

00:42:03.200 --> 00:42:09.280
[Guest]: in a rule of law manner and not in arbitrary manner that the founding happened and after that,

00:42:10.320 --> 00:42:15.120
[Guest]: we have in many ways diluted some of the rights. For example, the freedom of speech in India has

00:42:15.120 --> 00:42:22.880
[Guest]: had a really rough time to kind of put it mildly and many other rights have had a tough time over

00:42:22.880 --> 00:42:27.920
[Guest]: time. And it has been done in the name of these things only like the state has said, okay, we want

00:42:27.920 --> 00:42:32.320
[Guest]: to I want to preserve certain social order, but to be able to do that, some of the rights have to be,

00:42:32.320 --> 00:42:39.200
[Guest]: you know, compromised. In fact, original cases for I mean, in the pre-independence time,

00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:45.280
[Guest]: there were some communal riots and all because somebody published a book which was derogatory of

00:42:45.280 --> 00:42:52.800
[Guest]: one particular religions, sentiments and sort of so on and so forth. So, there has been this kind

00:42:52.800 --> 00:42:57.440
[Guest]: of tension in Indian politics. And Indian constitutional thought has also kind of been

00:42:57.440 --> 00:43:05.120
[Guest]: affected by this tension that how do you have a state which is actually kind of legitimized by

00:43:05.120 --> 00:43:11.120
[Guest]: democratic politics where you have this couple of problems with this kind of some communities

00:43:11.120 --> 00:43:16.000
[Guest]: which are significantly disadvantaged historically and some which in the because of their religious

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:20.720
[Guest]: identity may going forward be at a risk and it is not an easy question to answer.

00:43:20.720 --> 00:43:27.360
[Guest]: And it requires I mean, constant thinking and rethinking so that the society actually can deal

00:43:27.360 --> 00:43:33.760
[Guest]: with these issues in a manner that nobody is at significant disadvantage. And the legitimacy is

00:43:33.760 --> 00:43:40.560
[Guest]: not just of 60 70% majority, it is a wide based and if nation becomes habitable for everybody,

00:43:40.560 --> 00:43:46.560
[Guest]: that is the kind of objective that we need to have, but it has to be worked politically.

00:43:46.560 --> 00:43:52.640
[Guest]: So, I think when you say democracy and you say okay, such and such rights should be there or

00:43:52.640 --> 00:43:59.520
[Guest]: some special recognition should be there for some groups, then it has to happen through at least

00:43:59.520 --> 00:44:06.640
[Guest]: some measure of democratic agreement. Now, then it gets into the issue of majoritarianism or the

00:44:06.640 --> 00:44:12.720
[Guest]: potentiality. I am not saying that the majority is more of a threat that it may not actualize,

00:44:12.720 --> 00:44:17.520
[Guest]: but there is a potentiality that can happen and that depends on the kind of politics that we have

00:44:17.520 --> 00:44:22.160
[Guest]: and the kind of persuasion that is done. Because beyond a point, suppose you have some

00:44:22.160 --> 00:44:27.360
[Guest]: specific provisions in law or constitution which are not in line with what vast majority people

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:33.680
[Guest]: think and they have not been persuaded to think otherwise, then you have a tension which can blow

00:44:33.680 --> 00:44:40.320
[Guest]: up in many ways. So, politically because you also have the instruments of that kind of blowback

00:44:40.320 --> 00:44:46.560
[Guest]: right, because you have everybody in equal votes and there is an election and over time certain

00:44:46.560 --> 00:44:51.360
[Guest]: certain kind of resentment can crystallize in the form of support for some leaders or some parties

00:44:51.360 --> 00:44:56.320
[Guest]: or some kind of ideologies. And so, there is no alternative to continuous conversation and

00:44:56.320 --> 00:45:03.120
[Guest]: persuasion on these issues. What I do not think is particularly helpful is if you have people who

00:45:03.120 --> 00:45:08.480
[Guest]: think that they can go to a court and settle these kind of questions and not have some kind of a

00:45:09.040 --> 00:45:14.800
[Guest]: mobilization around it, some kind of a person attempt to persuade more and more people and speak

00:45:14.800 --> 00:45:20.080
[Guest]: to their better senses. Because when you do establish democracy, you have immediately on

00:45:20.080 --> 00:45:26.080
[Guest]: that day in some ways, in a very basic political equality was established that everybody is equal,

00:45:26.080 --> 00:45:31.360
[Guest]: everybody has one vote, everybody is a citizen. It is a very important event in itself. And that

00:45:31.360 --> 00:45:37.040
[Guest]: event has its own consequences. You know, it is not for the state to just look at the society and

00:45:37.040 --> 00:45:42.320
[Guest]: engineer it in this direction, that direction, that is also partially important. But let us look

00:45:42.320 --> 00:45:47.920
[Guest]: at the force of democracy itself. Like you say, okay, there is inequality, there is issues of

00:45:47.920 --> 00:45:52.560
[Guest]: majority minority and all of that. But when democracy says that everybody is equal and

00:45:52.560 --> 00:45:58.960
[Guest]: everybody is one vote, that itself has a certain kind of force and power in society. I do not know

00:45:58.960 --> 00:46:03.760
[Guest]: whether you have read Tocqueville and his democracy in America and how he describes democracy as a

00:46:04.480 --> 00:46:10.720
[Guest]: generative, you know, force, so to speak, that it has a certain kind of power of its own.

00:46:10.720 --> 00:46:16.480
[Guest]: I mean, it is not it works in a mild ways. It is not like the state which uses its kind of

00:46:16.480 --> 00:46:22.320
[Guest]: power and coercion. It has other ways that also needs to work. So, I think we need to have both

00:46:22.320 --> 00:46:29.280
[Guest]: of these tracks running where there is a certain politics and level of mobilization around certain

00:46:29.280 --> 00:46:38.240
[Guest]: ideas of equality and liberty. And you have a state where the executive and also the sometimes

00:46:38.240 --> 00:46:46.720
[Guest]: judiciary is intervening to correct specific kind of problems. But there is no shortcut to

00:46:46.720 --> 00:46:50.480
[Guest]: kind of just sidestepping the need for mobilization and persuasion.

00:46:50.480 --> 00:46:55.760
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, I will come back to the force of democracy later. But just thinking aloud from

00:46:55.760 --> 00:47:01.040
[Amit Varma]: the first part of what you were talking about, it seems to me that as a libertarian, there are

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:06.160
[Amit Varma]: two different clashes of ideas which worry me and which I cannot reconcile. One, of course,

00:47:06.160 --> 00:47:12.880
[Amit Varma]: is like what you said, constitutionalism. And one of the basic purposes of a constitution is to

00:47:12.880 --> 00:47:19.520
[Amit Varma]: a place a limit on state power and b protect individual rights, which is exactly my position.

00:47:19.520 --> 00:47:24.480
[Amit Varma]: That's what the constitution should do. But then I look at society and the thing is that

00:47:24.480 --> 00:47:29.520
[Amit Varma]: is society ready for that? Because leave aside the ancient example of Sati. If you just look at

00:47:29.520 --> 00:47:34.560
[Amit Varma]: modern India today, you'll see that there are Khab Panchayats and you'll see that there are honor

00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:40.080
[Amit Varma]: killings. And you'll see that society is still divided along these lines and that that division

00:47:40.080 --> 00:47:46.240
[Amit Varma]: is enforced by non state authorities and traditions and so on. And the thing is that

00:47:46.240 --> 00:47:51.520
[Amit Varma]: the fundamental on irreconcilable difference there is again between individual rights,

00:47:51.520 --> 00:47:56.560
[Amit Varma]: which I believe in, and in many cases, group rights, which some of these people would believe

00:47:56.560 --> 00:48:03.040
[Amit Varma]: in where a Khab Panchayat would think of the quote unquote interest of the group over that of

00:48:03.040 --> 00:48:07.760
[Amit Varma]: the individual or how they define the interest of the group. That's one conflict and I don't

00:48:07.760 --> 00:48:14.880
[Amit Varma]: have an easy answer for it. And the second sort of conflict that comes to my mind is one between

00:48:14.880 --> 00:48:21.920
[Amit Varma]: the constitution protecting individual rights, and between the constitution trying to redesign

00:48:21.920 --> 00:48:28.000
[Amit Varma]: society to transform society as it were, and the second involves infringing individual rights,

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:34.720
[Amit Varma]: usually in some way or the other. And here again, it becomes a question of group rights being given

00:48:34.720 --> 00:48:40.240
[Amit Varma]: precedence over individual rights, except where in my first example with Khab Panchayats and

00:48:40.240 --> 00:48:45.200
[Amit Varma]: honor killings, it's really the right which I'm fighting against. And in this case, it's really

00:48:45.200 --> 00:48:49.600
[Amit Varma]: the left I'm fighting against, which doesn't understand the futility of social engineering

00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:55.760
[Amit Varma]: and the kind of unintended consequences it can lead to. And the divisions that can be festered

00:48:55.760 --> 00:49:01.280
[Amit Varma]: by privileging group rights and thinking in terms of groups over individuals. I know it sounds like

00:49:01.280 --> 00:49:07.680
[Guest]: I'm rambling, but I just thought I'll… No, no. I don't think you're rambling. I also wrestle

00:49:07.680 --> 00:49:11.520
[Guest]: with these issues. We are all kind of thinking and these are not easy issues to deal with.

00:49:11.520 --> 00:49:15.760
[Guest]: But let's take them one by one in my, I'm just kind of trying to reflect in my own limited

00:49:15.760 --> 00:49:22.480
[Guest]: understanding of these things that so go back to the history of legal systems. So, before this

00:49:22.480 --> 00:49:29.760
[Guest]: kind of modern state came along, and the legislature makes the laws and executive,

00:49:29.760 --> 00:49:35.360
[Guest]: I mean, implements them and the judiciary then kind of give, looks at specific cases,

00:49:36.080 --> 00:49:40.880
[Guest]: where there's a violation of a law and kind of meets out punishments and so on and so forth.

00:49:40.880 --> 00:49:46.000
[Guest]: And also looks at laws that are unconstitutional and strikes them down to some degree of judicial

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:52.480
[Guest]: review and all of that. So, that's the modern, it's built on some, I mean, some version of legal

00:49:52.480 --> 00:49:58.880
[Guest]: positivism. There's some thinking that law is basically what humans make of it, you know,

00:49:58.880 --> 00:50:04.880
[Guest]: in some sense. And there's an assumption that some people come together, ideally elected and

00:50:04.880 --> 00:50:10.480
[Guest]: enjoying legitimacy of electoral victories and make those laws. And they can, so today, for

00:50:10.480 --> 00:50:14.320
[Guest]: example, you have something which is illegal. Tomorrow, the parliament can pass a law and make

00:50:14.320 --> 00:50:20.480
[Guest]: that legal. Right. And then when it's illegal, you have systems to enforce it and change it and

00:50:20.480 --> 00:50:26.720
[Guest]: so on and so forth. And if it's legal, you can do it. Before this system came along, we had more

00:50:26.720 --> 00:50:33.760
[Guest]: traditional law. And not just India, every society had had this kind of law and they were, of course,

00:50:33.760 --> 00:50:38.720
[Guest]: it was a mixed system. There also, there were some aspects of law that were some high kind of

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:43.920
[Guest]: council could sit and change. But most of the laws were just evolved over time. It was not like

00:50:43.920 --> 00:50:52.160
[Guest]: this some council can sit one day and change it. For example, Catholic religion has had reforms,

00:50:52.160 --> 00:50:57.600
[Guest]: right. The Vatican too sat down and made some changes, for example, very significantly they

00:50:58.480 --> 00:51:04.800
[Guest]: made the nuns, sisters equal to the laity, you know, they said they do not have any special

00:51:04.800 --> 00:51:11.360
[Guest]: place there in that sense in the church. So, they could make such changes, but most of the

00:51:11.360 --> 00:51:18.320
[Guest]: laws were evolved over time. And they were enforced through social, you know, means of

00:51:19.120 --> 00:51:25.280
[Guest]: partly nudging and partly coercing. And I would not say honor killing is something which is an

00:51:25.280 --> 00:51:29.760
[Guest]: example of that. But a Khaab Panchayat is in a sense. So, Khaab Panchayat, there's a lot of

00:51:29.760 --> 00:51:37.040
[Guest]: things, frankly. And not all of that is something which comes out because it's just mutually

00:51:37.040 --> 00:51:42.800
[Guest]: acceptable to different parties. You know, they are community based systems of conflict resolution,

00:51:42.800 --> 00:51:48.320
[Guest]: and they have been there for a very long time. They are still here. The tension here is this.

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:52.480
[Guest]: So, let me just kind of complete this particular thought about contrast between traditional law

00:51:52.480 --> 00:51:58.080
[Guest]: and legal positivism is that over time as legal positivism and this modern state has taken over,

00:51:58.080 --> 00:52:02.560
[Guest]: it has obviously crowded out traditional ways of making and implementing laws and

00:52:02.560 --> 00:52:07.760
[Guest]: it has made it difficult for societies to organize themselves around their own traditional

00:52:07.760 --> 00:52:13.600
[Guest]: laws and their own ways of enforcing those laws. Because, you know, you can have only one sheriff

00:52:13.600 --> 00:52:18.800
[Guest]: in town, so the state says that I am that and you can't do much. They tolerate a lot of it. So,

00:52:18.800 --> 00:52:23.600
[Guest]: when Khaab Panchayat do small stuff around property disputes and where there is somebody

00:52:23.600 --> 00:52:28.320
[Guest]: who claims and they can, as the community comes around and say, okay, this is, this person is

00:52:28.320 --> 00:52:33.920
[Guest]: right and the person accepts it and goes along, it's fine. 99% of the stuff you never hear of.

00:52:33.920 --> 00:52:38.080
[Guest]: But one person when it does come out, then you can see this conflict between the state and

00:52:38.080 --> 00:52:43.680
[Guest]: traditional law and traditional systems of enforcing those laws. So, there is this tension

00:52:43.680 --> 00:52:48.960
[Guest]: that has happened that it is, I mean, I do not know whether it is desirable, but certainly we

00:52:48.960 --> 00:52:55.920
[Guest]: are not there and that all the law is only made by the state or everything that is called law,

00:52:55.920 --> 00:53:01.200
[Guest]: law, I mean, the broadly sense on norms on all kind of distinguishable difference about

00:53:01.200 --> 00:53:04.960
[Guest]: is allowed and disallowed is only made by the state and only enforced by the state.

00:53:04.960 --> 00:53:11.600
[Guest]: And the early system was the only made by the society, so to speak, more or less. And there

00:53:11.600 --> 00:53:17.360
[Guest]: was, of course, this notion of a monarch or some kind of a state, which was when playing a part of

00:53:17.360 --> 00:53:22.400
[Guest]: that was a part of the system, it was not external to it. This modern state is external to it,

00:53:22.400 --> 00:53:27.360
[Guest]: it is separate and it is claiming the space that the society had. So, this creates these tensions

00:53:27.360 --> 00:53:32.960
[Guest]: that the society is not completely changed and become that evolved to become compliant with the

00:53:32.960 --> 00:53:38.400
[Guest]: state as such. It is always contested space. And when something like honor killing happens,

00:53:38.400 --> 00:53:43.280
[Guest]: it is a no brainer, right? Basic thing is you do not need to kill somebody like that.

00:53:43.920 --> 00:53:48.160
[Guest]: But most of the situations are not like that. There is much more subtle kind of coercion and

00:53:48.160 --> 00:53:54.160
[Guest]: subtle kind of nudges here and there, where it is not so obvious whether it should be in the

00:53:54.720 --> 00:54:01.280
[Guest]: social system of norm setting and enforcing or should the state do it. So, there are some

00:54:01.280 --> 00:54:06.800
[Guest]: no brainer examples that you just mentioned, but most of the cases are not like that. But

00:54:08.160 --> 00:54:14.560
[Guest]: the way you think, the way I think about it is that there are some basic kind of rights and

00:54:14.560 --> 00:54:18.560
[Guest]: protections that the constitution has given. There are laws that have been made in the constitution.

00:54:19.120 --> 00:54:24.880
[Guest]: As long as there is no conflict between the two, there is no problem. Society cannot

00:54:24.880 --> 00:54:30.320
[Guest]: kill somebody or put somebody in a communal jail or something like that. Those things are not.

00:54:30.320 --> 00:54:33.200
[Amit Varma]: If you do not allow them to steal from you, that is if you do not pay your taxes,

00:54:33.200 --> 00:54:38.560
[Guest]: then they will abduct you. Yeah. So, but now let us come to this.

00:54:38.560 --> 00:54:45.840
[Amit Varma]: But I will briefly interrupt here and this will not make you laugh, but I recently appeared on

00:54:45.840 --> 00:54:50.560
[Amit Varma]: an episode of the Hindi show Pulyabazi, where I spoke in Hindi, which will be linked from the

00:54:50.560 --> 00:54:55.040
[Amit Varma]: show notes, where I spoke about Hayek. And Hayek makes this very interesting distinction between

00:54:55.040 --> 00:55:00.240
[Amit Varma]: law and legislation, where he defines law as what would basically be defined as common law,

00:55:00.240 --> 00:55:07.040
[Amit Varma]: the way it emerged, where basically the state's job there is to codify the laws that already exist

00:55:07.040 --> 00:55:12.080
[Amit Varma]: in society. For example, it is a social norm that you cannot steal from someone, that you cannot

00:55:12.080 --> 00:55:16.880
[Amit Varma]: kill someone, that you cannot force someone to do something. And these become codified as laws

00:55:16.880 --> 00:55:21.440
[Amit Varma]: by the state, which is a function of the state, according to Hayek. And his point is that this

00:55:21.440 --> 00:55:28.000
[Amit Varma]: is the legitimate function. Laws are often in Hayek's words, confused with what he terms

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:34.560
[Amit Varma]: legislation, which is the quote unquote laws that states create to rule over others. For example,

00:55:34.560 --> 00:55:39.840
[Amit Varma]: you could say that, you know, a business needing 37 licenses to open up is really

00:55:39.840 --> 00:55:48.800
[Amit Varma]: legislation, not a law. And this is the state misusing its monopoly on power, monopoly on

00:55:48.800 --> 00:55:55.600
[Amit Varma]: violence for this. And Hayek's warning, therefore, is that a state will always stand the people who

00:55:55.600 --> 00:55:59.840
[Amit Varma]: are in a state after all human beings subject to the normal incentives and the state will always

00:55:59.840 --> 00:56:07.360
[Amit Varma]: stand to increase its power by increasing such legislation on its own behalf or on the behalf

00:56:07.360 --> 00:56:12.480
[Amit Varma]: of interest groups, which fund the parties which get to power. And that leads to a reduction

00:56:12.480 --> 00:56:20.880
[Amit Varma]: of freedom. And it's important for alert citizens to distinguish between law and legislation. And

00:56:20.880 --> 00:56:26.080
[Amit Varma]: again, I'm just thinking a lot, this just came to mind that, you know, in the same way as the

00:56:26.080 --> 00:56:30.880
[Amit Varma]: law against Sati was kind of welcomed by society because it's time had come, the striking down of

00:56:30.880 --> 00:56:35.440
[Guest]: 377 recently was I think, by and large welcomed by society. It's a no brainer.

00:56:35.440 --> 00:56:39.520
[Guest]: Resistance as such, it just took the, you know, the tip the balance in the right direction.

00:56:40.080 --> 00:56:44.240
[Guest]: And I would argue that the society was more or less ready with that.

00:56:44.240 --> 00:56:46.560
[Amit Varma]: Ready for it and 20 years ago, it wouldn't have happened.

00:56:46.560 --> 00:56:51.360
[Guest]: Now let me complete my previous kind of call you interjected. So now we are talking about two kind

00:56:51.360 --> 00:56:56.240
[Guest]: of autonomous systems. One is this kind of social norms setting and enforcement and there's a state

00:56:57.280 --> 00:57:03.920
[Guest]: legislation law and enforcement of that. The most important tension is here. If the state tries to

00:57:03.920 --> 00:57:10.160
[Guest]: do too much of this with the society that is trying to crowd out completely all ways of in

00:57:10.160 --> 00:57:15.360
[Guest]: which society makes its norms and kind of enforces them, there's a risk that the society might

00:57:15.360 --> 00:57:21.520
[Guest]: capture the legal system, so to speak and say there's enough mobilization, which is of a

00:57:21.520 --> 00:57:27.360
[Guest]: reactionary kind. So I would say that this is a continuous kind of balance to be struck.

00:57:27.360 --> 00:57:34.160
[Guest]: But it would be less than ideal for the society if this goes in the direction where

00:57:34.160 --> 00:57:41.200
[Guest]: there's a big reactionary kind of movement which says that nothing doing now, we will just capture

00:57:41.200 --> 00:57:46.960
[Guest]: the system. I mean, through the means in which you capture the state by mobilizing through

00:57:47.680 --> 00:57:49.600
[Amit Varma]: elections and through getting.

00:57:49.600 --> 00:57:52.960
[Amit Varma]: Can you spell out in concrete terms what something like this could look like?

00:57:54.000 --> 00:57:56.640
[Guest]: No, so I'm just saying that this is not concrete.

00:57:56.640 --> 00:57:58.560
[Amit Varma]: This is the abstract expression.

00:57:58.560 --> 00:58:03.600
[Guest]: Abstract expression that I'm talking about two autonomous, semi autonomous systems. There's a

00:58:03.600 --> 00:58:08.160
[Guest]: legal system which is based on this. Basically, I mean, I'm oversimplifying, but

00:58:08.160 --> 00:58:12.160
[Guest]: this system of legal positivism where laws are what we make.

00:58:12.160 --> 00:58:12.880
[Amit Varma]: No, I get your point.

00:58:12.880 --> 00:58:18.160
[Guest]: And the other is this traditional law of that. And if you intervene too much on the former

00:58:18.160 --> 00:58:22.880
[Guest]: in a manner that is totally unacceptable to society time and again, you have a risk that this

00:58:22.880 --> 00:58:27.440
[Guest]: system will be mobilized to take over and implement its own ideas into this.

00:58:28.160 --> 00:58:31.440
[Amit Varma]: I agree with you, which is why I'm asking, can you illustrate that for me,

00:58:31.440 --> 00:58:34.800
[Amit Varma]: either with a hypothetical example or when it's really happened that way?

00:58:34.800 --> 00:58:39.520
[Guest]: So, I think it's better to talk about examples which have happened elsewhere.

00:58:39.520 --> 00:58:46.080
[Guest]: So, if you look at the issues of in the mobilization of religious conservatives in America,

00:58:47.360 --> 00:58:52.480
[Guest]: it was a part of the conservative industrial movement in America since the mid 20th century.

00:58:52.480 --> 00:58:57.200
[Guest]: And it found its crystallization in the form of different individuals and different kind of

00:58:57.200 --> 00:59:03.520
[Guest]: ideologies and so on and so forth. But the way it is kind of mobilized around the issue of say

00:59:03.520 --> 00:59:09.840
[Guest]: abortion, like it was a part of traditional law to so to speak that, you know, in their

00:59:09.840 --> 00:59:15.520
[Guest]: kind of religious tradition, this sanctity of life from inception, so to speak.

00:59:16.080 --> 00:59:22.240
[Guest]: And now it has become a part of the political discourse, because state has said that there is

00:59:22.240 --> 00:59:29.040
[Guest]: some it has a view on it. And I'm just giving you a comparative example. And there's one side of it,

00:59:29.040 --> 00:59:35.280
[Guest]: which has focused on women's rights and their sovereignty over their own bodies and so forth.

00:59:35.280 --> 00:59:40.720
[Guest]: And the religious conservatives, mainly and there are some other allies there also

00:59:41.920 --> 00:59:46.560
[Guest]: say that, no, we should not and there is a sanctity of life and so forth. Recently,

00:59:46.560 --> 00:59:51.040
[Guest]: they have passed some law in one of the states where abortion is six weeks is illegal and so on

00:59:51.040 --> 00:59:55.120
[Guest]: and so forth. So, they are then attempted by society to now capture and try to intervene in

00:59:55.120 --> 01:00:00.160
[Guest]: this and say that this is just one specific example. No, it's a great example. But it can

01:00:00.160 --> 01:00:06.160
[Guest]: happen at a large scale also, that the whole nature of the state might be transformed over time

01:00:06.160 --> 01:00:11.920
[Guest]: in a to a reactionary movement. And there's a dialectic at work here, which we have to be

01:00:11.920 --> 01:00:17.680
[Guest]: mindful of. And there's always a balance to be struck between trying to reform somebody while

01:00:17.680 --> 01:00:22.560
[Guest]: telling them that they are equal citizens and they have equal powers as everybody else. And

01:00:22.560 --> 01:00:28.560
[Guest]: also tolerating some things which may not be totally repugnant and may be allowed for some

01:00:28.560 --> 01:00:32.720
[Guest]: time to change on their own. So, I don't think there's a simple answer to this question.

01:00:32.720 --> 01:00:37.360
[Amit Varma]: No, it's a fantastic example, because it totally illustrates what, you know, like being libertarian,

01:00:37.360 --> 01:00:43.760
[Amit Varma]: I'm obviously pro choice and the autonomy of the woman is everything to me. But I can also get why

01:00:43.760 --> 01:00:47.520
[Amit Varma]: someone who believes in group rights over individual rights would say that no, that, you

01:00:47.520 --> 01:00:52.560
[Amit Varma]: know, we need to preserve every human life and the autonomy of the individual doesn't matter as

01:00:52.560 --> 01:00:58.800
[Guest]: long as we impose our values. Yeah, it's not just religiously, Peter Singer, once he gave an

01:00:58.800 --> 01:01:03.600
[Guest]: example of his philosopher friend, who is absolutely liberal and everything. I mean, on the left

01:01:03.600 --> 01:01:08.480
[Guest]: liberal side, but on abortion, he's, you can't have a conversation with him. He says that, hey,

01:01:09.040 --> 01:01:15.120
[Guest]: this life is human life, how can you end it on your own choice. So, there are these other non

01:01:15.120 --> 01:01:19.520
[Guest]: religious kind of people also who on that particular issue may have a different view.

01:01:19.520 --> 01:01:24.480
[Guest]: So, you can find allies, you can mobilize and all that. But this is an example of a specific issue.

01:01:25.040 --> 01:01:31.200
[Guest]: But I was referring to a wholesale takeover, which I mean, then you kind of get unmoved from the

01:01:31.760 --> 01:01:36.400
[Guest]: traditions on which modern state is built. The main point is, there has to be persuasion and

01:01:36.400 --> 01:01:43.920
[Guest]: mobilization and conversation at a broader level in society than in a courtroom or with a few kind

01:01:43.920 --> 01:01:48.640
[Guest]: of politicians who have power through anti-defection law, not the power of actual

01:01:48.640 --> 01:01:54.480
[Guest]: convincing even their MPs. So, these systems of which weaken our democracy, weaken the power of

01:01:54.480 --> 01:01:59.920
[Guest]: democratic functioning of society, I think are actually doing a disservice to our potential

01:01:59.920 --> 01:02:05.120
[Guest]: as a society in which to quote James Baldwin, you know, achieving our country.

01:02:06.640 --> 01:02:10.560
[Amit Varma]: I mean, people would disagree about what our country is to begin with. So, what do we achieve?

01:02:10.560 --> 01:02:16.320
[Guest]: Achieving means achieving what we could be, you know, as a look at the potential that we have as

01:02:16.320 --> 01:02:22.400
[Guest]: a multicultural society. Nobody gave India a good chance in 1940, 1947, 1950. Look at what

01:02:22.400 --> 01:02:27.600
[Guest]: churches said about us and many other supposedly intelligent people said about us. And I mean,

01:02:27.600 --> 01:02:32.320
[Guest]: we have surprised them in many ways, you know. So, we have a potential of achieving a really

01:02:32.320 --> 01:02:35.920
[Amit Varma]: great country. What I meant was there are so many different ideas of India out there that even the

01:02:35.920 --> 01:02:38.320
[Guest]: phrase achieving our country would mean different things to different people.

01:02:38.320 --> 01:02:42.800
[Guest]: I agree. I agree with that. It's just that, as we discussed earlier, there's a certain

01:02:42.800 --> 01:02:47.360
[Guest]: kind of irreconcilability and differences. But I'm talking from a point of view of

01:02:47.360 --> 01:02:52.080
[Guest]: certain kind of idealism about potentially people can agree on some things, you know,

01:02:52.080 --> 01:02:57.120
[Guest]: like, for example, the nation should be livable for everybody, something like that. People can

01:02:57.120 --> 01:03:01.600
[Guest]: disagree on that. I can see that. And but we should have a conversation about why that

01:03:01.600 --> 01:03:06.400
[Amit Varma]: disagreement is. I think a broad area of disagreement would be you and I would say

01:03:06.400 --> 01:03:10.240
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, multiculturalism and the diversity that we have is one of our great

01:03:10.240 --> 01:03:13.840
[Amit Varma]: strengths and we should embrace it. And that is what is going to make us a great country while

