[Amit Varma]: And the fundamental point there and no matter what you think of bread, but politics,

01:05:39.840 --> 01:05:45.280
[Amit Varma]: I think it's an important insight is that whatever change happens, social change happens first

01:05:45.280 --> 01:05:51.600
[Amit Varma]: happens in the culture and then it finds a political expression. How true do you think this

01:05:51.600 --> 01:05:57.760
[Guest]: is? I think it's quite true. I mean, it's not as true as saying that it's downstream and there's

01:05:57.760 --> 01:06:02.880
[Guest]: no nothing that goes the other way. It's that's not quite true. But substantially, yes, it's

01:06:02.880 --> 01:06:08.320
[Guest]: downstream from culture. And I remember reading somewhere Hannah Arendt is one said that

01:06:08.320 --> 01:06:17.680
[Guest]: every generation we are invaded by barbarians. We call them children. So and then they're not

01:06:17.680 --> 01:06:22.640
[Guest]: barbarians, but they're instinctual beings and who are who do have something in it. They're not

01:06:22.640 --> 01:06:31.040
[Guest]: blank slates. But then on that there's a lot of process of civilizing and telling them what's

01:06:31.040 --> 01:06:37.200
[Guest]: right and wrong and telling them I mean, kind of letting them be also but also kind of giving them

01:06:37.200 --> 01:06:43.520
[Guest]: some sense of what is I think children in flights and restaurants are barbarians, but I mean,

01:06:43.520 --> 01:06:51.760
[Amit Varma]: you're a doting parent and I'm very anti having children. So there is that that in this in the

01:06:51.760 --> 01:06:57.280
[Guest]: culture, this kind of value certain values are preserved and certain things are considered good

01:06:57.280 --> 01:07:03.040
[Guest]: some things are considered not good some things are tolerated something celebrated a lot of that

01:07:03.040 --> 01:07:10.800
[Guest]: happens and politics draws a lot from it. But I would argue that there is often also an

01:07:10.800 --> 01:07:15.680
[Guest]: opportunity for example, for statesmen for people who are political leaders, but they transcend

01:07:15.680 --> 01:07:22.720
[Guest]: just politics of appeasement and politics of pandering to actually shape culture and

01:07:22.720 --> 01:07:29.920
[Guest]: shape societal values, take very big risks and put their values out and kind of change the way

01:07:29.920 --> 01:07:36.000
[Guest]: people think about some issues. So I mean, at the top of my mind is someone like say Gandhi,

01:07:36.560 --> 01:07:44.560
[Guest]: someone like Lincoln, you know, who people who even I mean, I would argue people who I mean,

01:07:44.560 --> 01:07:50.160
[Guest]: not good example, I would say, but if you take bad examples and someone like Lenin, for example,

01:07:51.280 --> 01:07:55.520
[Amit Varma]: through politics, or an interesting example of someone I think who otherwise has been a bad

01:07:55.520 --> 01:08:00.000
[Amit Varma]: politician, I had Salman shows on the show recently and I asked him what he likes about

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:04.880
[Amit Varma]: Modi. And one of the things was Modi's focus on Swachh Bharat, where his point was that

01:08:04.880 --> 01:08:09.280
[Amit Varma]: whether or not he actually implements any Swachh Bharat policies, the fact that he's

01:08:09.280 --> 01:08:13.200
[Amit Varma]: praising it and making it a part of the discourse can have a positive impact on the culture.

01:08:14.080 --> 01:08:19.840
[Guest]: Yeah, it can. So the way what has happened over time is that politics is everywhere,

01:08:19.840 --> 01:08:25.600
[Guest]: everywhere, or will saw that coming 70 years ago, everything is now political, he wrote.

01:08:26.880 --> 01:08:31.440
[Guest]: So anybody who rises in politics and becomes very, very powerful, someone as popular as say,

01:08:31.440 --> 01:08:40.240
[Guest]: Mr. Modi has the opportunity to influence not just politics, but also culture in some ways.

01:08:40.240 --> 01:08:45.680
[Guest]: And it may happen in an indirect and unseen ways. It may happen over time, but just as process of,

01:08:45.680 --> 01:08:47.200
[Guest]: you know, myth of the hero, or

01:08:47.200 --> 01:08:51.760
[Amit Varma]: And it's part of it like the nature of celebrity in the sense that you could say for many people,

01:08:51.760 --> 01:08:55.840
[Amit Varma]: Modi is in politics, what Tendulkar is in cricket. So it's the same kind of influence

01:08:55.840 --> 01:09:00.080
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that Modi is impactful, not necessarily because he's like he has an

01:09:00.080 --> 01:09:04.800
[Amit Varma]: important position, but because he's a celebrity in politics in the same way that Sachin Tendulkar

01:09:04.800 --> 01:09:09.360
[Amit Varma]: is a celebrity in cricket or Amitabh Bachchan is a celebrity in cinema. So the words carry.

01:09:09.360 --> 01:09:16.000
[Guest]: I think it's a different category, because of the way politics is thought of and much more in

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:22.080
[Guest]: practice now. But even someone like Aristotle saw politics as the highest level in system of

01:09:22.080 --> 01:09:26.880
[Guest]: human knowledge, something that actually arbitrates between different other forms of

01:09:26.880 --> 01:09:33.520
[Guest]: knowledge and systems of value and so on and so forth. So it's a different level. And it has

01:09:33.520 --> 01:09:38.400
[Guest]: the ability to change much more than someone like Tendulkar for example, I don't know whether

01:09:38.400 --> 01:09:39.840
[Guest]: people look up to Tendulkar for

01:09:39.840 --> 01:09:41.040
[Amit Varma]: There were temples to him.

01:09:41.040 --> 01:09:48.240
[Guest]: Ha, maybe one or two. And, but whether they look up to him for kind of substantive questions

01:09:48.240 --> 01:09:54.400
[Guest]: of values and questions of, you know, culture and all I don't know, there are some who might do

01:09:54.400 --> 01:09:59.680
[Guest]: that. But much more that happens with popular political leaders, they have some ability,

01:09:59.680 --> 01:10:05.520
[Guest]: and whether they use that ability as statesmen or they don't use it is up to them. But they do

01:10:05.520 --> 01:10:11.360
[Guest]: have some of this ability to, if there's a tension in society, I recommend this book by Harry Jaffa,

01:10:11.360 --> 01:10:17.200
[Guest]: Crisis of the House Divided, which is between the Lincoln-Douglas debates, he's analyzing

01:10:17.200 --> 01:10:22.400
[Guest]: through the prism of the Declaration of Independence and the US Constitution, but

01:10:22.400 --> 01:10:30.240
[Guest]: mostly the Declaration of Independence, about how the Lincoln's stance in that was revealing of

01:10:30.240 --> 01:10:36.000
[Guest]: the nature of American Republic, you know, and you can't have a house that is divided around

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:44.560
[Guest]: something as basic as that. So, as something like slavery, for example, so he could tip the balance

01:10:44.560 --> 01:10:48.400
[Guest]: in the right direction. There was tension, I'm not saying that society was totally pro-slavery,

01:10:48.400 --> 01:10:53.520
[Guest]: and he could just turn that around, that is very difficult to do by one person in one lifetime or

01:10:53.520 --> 01:11:00.320
[Guest]: even some few years. But if there is tension, somebody can, through the charisma and through

01:11:00.320 --> 01:11:05.120
[Guest]: the ability to move people, change the way they look at things, also conflict, when he went to

01:11:05.120 --> 01:11:09.600
[Guest]: war, right, he went to civil war, hundreds of thousands of Americans laid down their lives

01:11:11.280 --> 01:11:17.440
[Guest]: to overthrow the, I mean to change, abolish slavery in some ways. So, that is also possible.

01:11:17.440 --> 01:11:24.400
[Guest]: But substantially, it's true that, I mean, culture is upstream of politics, and we do get

01:11:24.960 --> 01:11:27.840
[Guest]: the politics that in a way, the culture determines.

01:11:27.840 --> 01:11:32.480
[Amit Varma]: So, let me bring you now to a subject, which I know you've thought about very deeply,

01:11:33.360 --> 01:11:38.400
[Amit Varma]: which is the role of religion in politics, because if we again talk about the essential

01:11:38.400 --> 01:11:43.520
[Amit Varma]: conflict between, say, the state and the society, and one of the ways in which it plays out, and it

01:11:43.520 --> 01:11:49.760
[Amit Varma]: plays out in the context of India, definitely, is that we are set up as a secular state. And you

01:11:49.760 --> 01:11:54.640
[Amit Varma]: could say, again, this is the result of a statesman driving change in a manner of speaking,

01:11:54.640 --> 01:12:01.840
[Amit Varma]: because it was really Nehru's vision that stood out over those of others in his party who had

01:12:01.840 --> 01:12:07.840
[Amit Varma]: slightly different visions. But for what it's worth, we are a secular state, and thank goodness

01:12:07.840 --> 01:12:12.640
[Amit Varma]: for that, because that in a sense, to me, is something that gives space for diversity to

01:12:12.640 --> 01:12:19.680
[Amit Varma]: flourish. But a there's been pushback against that in terms of how secular it really is.

01:12:19.680 --> 01:12:24.240
[Amit Varma]: I mean, one of the like I had an episode on Hindutva with Akhar Patel. And one of the

01:12:24.240 --> 01:12:29.680
[Amit Varma]: contradictions I asked him about is that earlier the BJP used to accuse the Congress of not being

01:12:29.680 --> 01:12:34.800
[Amit Varma]: truly secular, but pandering to the minorities and doing what it called pseudo secularism.

01:12:34.800 --> 01:12:39.600
[Amit Varma]: But then when they use the phrase pseudo secular, you assume that they have a problem with it,

01:12:39.600 --> 01:12:45.120
[Amit Varma]: because it is pseudo. But they also have a problem with secularism, which kind of baffles

01:12:45.120 --> 01:12:51.520
[Amit Varma]: me. But to cut a rambling question short, I think that the role of religion in society and

01:12:51.520 --> 01:12:57.520
[Amit Varma]: in politics is something you've kind of thought a lot about. Tell me how this sort of fault line

01:12:57.520 --> 01:13:00.160
[Amit Varma]: has evolved in the last 70 years. And where are we today?

01:13:00.160 --> 01:13:07.120
[Guest]: I'm not an expert on this issue at all. But my inquiry is not so much in my thinking and

01:13:07.120 --> 01:13:13.040
[Guest]: reading has not been about role of religion in politics as such, but more about religion in

01:13:13.040 --> 01:13:20.080
[Guest]: modern society and kind of what kinds of role it can play and what are the ways in which it

01:13:20.080 --> 01:13:25.360
[Guest]: might transform, it is transforming and what are the new forms that it is taking more of that.

01:13:25.360 --> 01:13:32.640
[Guest]: And part of it is, of course, to do with the politics of religion. And in some ways,

01:13:32.640 --> 01:13:38.080
[Guest]: what people call religion of politics. Also, I don't know whether this philosopher Eric

01:13:38.080 --> 01:13:43.280
[Guest]: Vogelin has his book called political religions in which he argues somewhat persuasively,

01:13:43.280 --> 01:13:49.200
[Guest]: but really is that in modern ideologies are the new religions. I mean, he was he

01:13:49.200 --> 01:13:53.040
[Guest]: has been criticized significantly. It's not a settled position, you know.

01:13:53.040 --> 01:13:53.840
[Guest]: What's your position?

01:13:54.400 --> 01:13:58.640
[Guest]: So, yeah, so the political ideologies do have some kind of

01:13:58.640 --> 01:14:04.400
[Guest]: appease to our kind of need for community, need for meaning and all which earlier

01:14:04.400 --> 01:14:09.040
[Guest]: religions did have fulfilled. So, there is something to that. Parts of religion do,

01:14:09.040 --> 01:14:14.160
[Guest]: politics does, political kind of movements and part of political ideologies do work,

01:14:14.160 --> 01:14:20.960
[Guest]: I mean, in some ways like religion, but they are not religion, they are different category.

01:14:20.960 --> 01:14:26.000
[Guest]: You know, all authority is not the same, you know, like religious authority is very different

01:14:26.000 --> 01:14:30.640
[Guest]: from political authority. So, and what you seek in religion is very different.

01:14:30.640 --> 01:14:34.400
[Guest]: When people see different things in religion, there's not one thing, but all those things put

01:14:34.400 --> 01:14:39.680
[Guest]: together are not the same as what you see through politics. So, there are different categories,

01:14:39.680 --> 01:14:43.200
[Guest]: but there is, I mean, they do appeal in some ways to our similar kind of desires. So,

01:14:43.200 --> 01:14:47.440
[Guest]: there are variations of that. So, I'm still thinking about how to put it.

01:14:48.000 --> 01:14:53.840
[Guest]: Now, the other part, which is the politics of religion, right, about where we are. So,

01:14:53.840 --> 01:15:00.080
[Guest]: the view that was taken in Indian constitution is not of American style separation of church and

01:15:00.080 --> 01:15:04.400
[Guest]: state, that we don't have. In fact, very few countries in the world have that kind of separation

01:15:04.400 --> 01:15:07.360
[Guest]: of church and state. Which is a classic traditional meaning of secular, right?

01:15:08.240 --> 01:15:12.800
[Guest]: No, so, this is very rare actually to see total separation of church and state.

01:15:12.800 --> 01:15:16.560
[Guest]: Okay. For example, Sweden until year 2000 had

01:15:16.560 --> 01:15:22.720
[Guest]: the state subsidized church. So, it is a very secular society, but until just 19 years ago,

01:15:22.720 --> 01:15:28.480
[Guest]: they had a state subsidized church, Lutheran Church. So, Europe doesn't have that. I mean,

01:15:28.480 --> 01:15:33.280
[Guest]: it has gone through many stages and it doesn't have that, it has a fairly, I mean, in effect,

01:15:33.280 --> 01:15:38.800
[Guest]: it has a very secular state. But in at least de jure, there's a lot more of, you know,

01:15:38.800 --> 01:15:45.520
[Guest]: religious, religion in politics and politics and religion are intertwined. So, in our stance,

01:15:45.520 --> 01:15:50.480
[Guest]: as one thinker on this has written is more of a principle distance, that we will keep

01:15:50.480 --> 01:15:56.400
[Guest]: a distance from religion, but we will make principle interventions. So, on things like

01:15:56.400 --> 01:16:04.960
[Guest]: some issues of rights and things of temple entry, marriage and some specific issues on

01:16:04.960 --> 01:16:14.080
[Guest]: which we will intervene and make change, try to reform religion, but we will otherwise

01:16:14.080 --> 01:16:19.280
[Guest]: keep a principle distance. So, there has been that and it's been mostly, I mean, looking

01:16:19.280 --> 01:16:25.840
[Guest]: at Hinduism as a religion, much more, obviously, because of the nature of the founding and

01:16:25.840 --> 01:16:30.880
[Guest]: all of that, they have looked at Hinduism more from the point of view of reform by state

01:16:30.880 --> 01:16:36.160
[Guest]: intervention. So, other religions have had and Hinduism, they have defined very broadly,

01:16:36.160 --> 01:16:39.440
[Guest]: it's not just Hindus, Buddhists and Jains and all sorts of the constitutions defined

01:16:39.440 --> 01:16:45.120
[Guest]: including that. So, that has been, that was the founding moment and over time, it has

01:16:45.120 --> 01:16:51.360
[Guest]: led to many laws and judicial cases and all of that which have kind of built on that most

01:16:51.360 --> 01:16:57.520
[Guest]: recently being the Sabarimala case, all of that. So, over time it has happened and there

01:16:57.520 --> 01:17:01.920
[Guest]: has been a basic argument is that we have some minimum standards as a constitutional

01:17:01.920 --> 01:17:08.320
[Guest]: republic over rights and in certain situations we can, so they built this essential practice

01:17:08.320 --> 01:17:13.520
[Guest]: doctrine. They said unless it's an essential practice, we can intervene and change that

01:17:13.520 --> 01:17:17.760
[Guest]: in the name of consistency with the constitutional principles, so to speak. I am not a lawyer,

01:17:17.760 --> 01:17:23.040
[Guest]: so I am talking about it loosely, but they built that doctrine and they built other kind

01:17:23.040 --> 01:17:29.360
[Guest]: of jurisprudence around it, the courts did. And so, that has been a long journey and it

01:17:29.360 --> 01:17:35.840
[Guest]: is still continuing as we saw in Sabarimala and all that. And so, there is a view that

01:17:36.480 --> 01:17:41.840
[Guest]: politics has a role in what religion should be and this is politics, right, the state

01:17:41.840 --> 01:17:48.560
[Guest]: is a political being. And I think it has many, many kind of consequences. We do not

01:17:48.560 --> 01:17:52.560
[Guest]: know what those consequences specifically are, but it will certainly has some consequences

01:17:52.560 --> 01:17:55.760
[Guest]: about the interest that religion takes into the state then, right.

01:17:55.760 --> 01:18:01.760
[Guest]: Because if you say that, okay, the religion can be changed by state power, then people

01:18:01.760 --> 01:18:08.080
[Guest]: who are mobilizing around religious identities and religious kind of themes will say that

01:18:08.080 --> 01:18:14.480
[Guest]: now we have a greater incentive to come and take power and make sure that those interventions

01:18:14.480 --> 01:18:17.840
[Guest]: are minimized or something like that. There is a politics of that, I mean, it has to be

01:18:17.840 --> 01:18:22.480
[Guest]: fought and there is a contest there. It is not something which is settled and it will

01:18:22.480 --> 01:18:28.160
[Guest]: go in one way or the other. But if you look at it broadly around the world, what has happened

01:18:28.160 --> 01:18:35.680
[Guest]: is that in Western Europe, religion has, Western Europe, Northern Europe, religions have declined

01:18:35.680 --> 01:18:43.920
[Guest]: very substantially. Secularization is a process that they call. China, it is hard to say because

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:50.400
[Guest]: the state is an atheist state. So, if you do surveys, you do not ever get a word value

01:18:50.400 --> 01:18:54.640
[Guest]: service as 3% Chinese say they are religious, but in practice, they may be more. So, we

01:18:54.640 --> 01:18:58.720
[Guest]: do not know what it is. But for the rest of the world, there is considerable amount of

01:18:58.720 --> 01:19:04.320
[Guest]: religiosity, I mean, it varies a lot across the world and US is an exception, for example.

01:19:04.320 --> 01:19:10.160
[Guest]: US has among advanced countries, you will see less religion generally, but US has more

01:19:10.160 --> 01:19:17.200
[Guest]: religiosity reducing slowly, but has much more religiosity. But wherever there is a

01:19:17.200 --> 01:19:23.280
[Guest]: great deal of religious religiosity, this quotation is much greater because this kind

01:19:23.280 --> 01:19:30.320
[Guest]: of question of the legal system versus the religious law and religious practices is much

01:19:30.320 --> 01:19:34.640
[Guest]: greater. India is one of those. So, if you look at the surveys of India, India is one

01:19:34.640 --> 01:19:39.440
[Guest]: of the most religious societies in the world. Like if you look at the comparable across

01:19:39.440 --> 01:19:44.560
[Guest]: the world where they look at the same question across countries, more than 90% Indians say

01:19:44.560 --> 01:19:49.920
[Guest]: that religion is important to their identity. So, it becomes much more important in our

01:19:49.920 --> 01:19:53.920
[Guest]: context because we have not, and it has increased over time. So, religiosity has increased over

01:19:53.920 --> 01:19:53.920
[Amit Varma]: time.

01:19:53.920 --> 01:19:55.520
[Amit Varma]: Why do you think it has increased over time?

01:19:55.520 --> 01:20:01.120
[Guest]: That is very, it is something that social scientists have to study and answer, but it

01:20:01.120 --> 01:20:05.440
[Guest]: is something which could have many reasons. So, if I were to look at, so I some time ago

01:20:05.440 --> 01:20:10.000
[Guest]: did a review of literature on secularization, political science, sociology and historic

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:14.320
[Guest]: history. I mean, these are different methods through which people have studied it. So,

01:20:14.320 --> 01:20:18.480
[Guest]: there are different reasons why they explain, I mean, they explain away how secularization

01:20:18.480 --> 01:20:23.040
[Guest]: happens and why religion declines and all of that. Most of these accounts are kind of

01:20:23.040 --> 01:20:27.040
[Guest]: one or two variable accounts simplistic. So, but there is some explanatory power in

01:20:27.040 --> 01:20:32.960
[Guest]: them. So, for example, one of the leading political science books on this is Sacred

01:20:32.960 --> 01:20:39.680
[Guest]: and the Secular by Pepper Norris and Ronald Englehart. And their main thing is that,

01:20:39.680 --> 01:20:44.880
[Guest]: their thesis is that the secure societies, people who feel more secure, they do not,

01:20:45.440 --> 01:20:50.000
[Guest]: they face less risk. I mean, there are different type of risks that they differentiate,

01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:54.800
[Guest]: the egotropic risk, which is to yourself and your family and sociotropic risks, which are

01:20:54.800 --> 01:21:00.720
[Guest]: to the community. If they face more of those risks, then you are likely to be more religious.

01:21:00.720 --> 01:21:04.000
[Guest]: If you feel less of this risk, which is the case mostly in advanced countries,

01:21:04.000 --> 01:21:10.240
[Guest]: you face less of this religiosity. So, you see increase in religiosity in US after 9-11,

01:21:10.240 --> 01:21:16.320
[Guest]: because the community was at risk, so to speak. Then there is someone, other theorists like

01:21:16.320 --> 01:21:22.960
[Guest]: sociologist Rodney Stark and his kind of associates have written up about how religion,

01:21:23.600 --> 01:21:29.360
[Guest]: which thrives on competition, the multiple religions in the same society, then you have

01:21:29.360 --> 01:21:33.840
[Guest]: more chances of religiosity rising because you are always reminded of the difference and there

01:21:33.840 --> 01:21:37.920
[Guest]: is an incentive for organized religion to put itself out there and keep its flock.

01:21:37.920 --> 01:21:46.080
[Guest]: So, I am just trying to look at the different possibilities. Then if you look at some recent

01:21:46.080 --> 01:21:52.480
[Guest]: book I read on secularization in UK, Britain, then Callum Brown is a historian who wrote his

01:21:53.520 --> 01:21:57.360
[Guest]: body of work on secularization in British society. He is one of the, some interesting

01:21:57.360 --> 01:22:03.920
[Guest]: account he has written, but his central point is the increased participation of women in workforce.

01:22:03.920 --> 01:22:08.880
[Guest]: So, he says that women played a very central role in religious life of the British society,

01:22:08.880 --> 01:22:13.920
[Guest]: which kind of organizing, being the more, the organizing person in the family to make sure

01:22:13.920 --> 01:22:16.960
[Guest]: everybody is going to church and all of that and being…

01:22:16.960 --> 01:22:19.200
[Amit Varma]: Pooja at home and all that.

01:22:19.200 --> 01:22:21.680
[Amit Varma]: Not they didn't do pooja, but they…

01:22:21.680 --> 01:22:23.600
[Amit Varma]: In India, I am thinking of this context.

01:22:23.600 --> 01:22:28.000
[Guest]: I am talking about those, that region, not India. This is all from different other countries.

01:22:28.000 --> 01:22:31.760
[Guest]: And he says that as in the 60s, there was a big increase in

01:22:33.440 --> 01:22:39.280
[Guest]: female work level for participation and this he calls de-pietization of femininity. It's a term

01:22:39.280 --> 01:22:46.560
[Guest]: that he is kind of praise that he has created. And that led, there was a significant factor in

01:22:46.560 --> 01:22:53.200
[Guest]: secularization of the British society. Then there are other books, I mean, there are Steve Bruce and

01:22:54.480 --> 01:22:59.280
[Guest]: David Martin, their books on how if there are some societies in which there is a need for

01:22:59.280 --> 01:23:05.360
[Guest]: cultural defense. So, for example, the Irish nationalism and Catholicism are very intertwined,

01:23:05.360 --> 01:23:10.400
[Guest]: because Irish nationality is very much built on the Catholic identity. So, there also,

01:23:10.400 --> 01:23:15.600
[Guest]: until they are under siege, right, there is a nationalist movement to separate and all of that.

01:23:16.400 --> 01:23:22.720
[Guest]: So, that feeds religion. The different ways in which people have described why religions

01:23:22.720 --> 01:23:28.240
[Guest]: rise or fall in societies. And I feel many of these factors in India are quite true. I mean,

01:23:28.240 --> 01:23:31.120
[Guest]: if I were to just think about it in a very simplistic way, social science doesn't work that

01:23:31.120 --> 01:23:37.520
[Guest]: way. But I am a student, I am not an expert on these issues. But I mean, our female labor for

01:23:37.520 --> 01:23:41.840
[Guest]: participation has fallen significantly over the last 10 years. We are a very insecure society,

01:23:41.840 --> 01:23:47.520
[Guest]: there's a lot of poverty, a lot of egotropic and sociotropic risks. We as a people are often kind

01:23:47.520 --> 01:23:53.600
[Guest]: of feel that we are under threat from both sides of our borders. Then if you were to kind of go

01:23:53.600 --> 01:23:59.280
[Guest]: beyond these political science and sociological accounts and get into the philosophical argument

01:23:59.280 --> 01:24:08.400
[Guest]: about change in the social imaginary, about how non-religion or atheism becomes a viable option,

01:24:08.400 --> 01:24:13.280
[Guest]: there's a journey that societies go through, which in the West they went through, for example,

01:24:13.280 --> 01:24:18.640
[Guest]: Charles Taylor is very insightful on this. He wrote a book called Secular Age, which is, I think,

01:24:18.640 --> 01:24:24.320
[Guest]: the most insightful account on this that I have read about how the philosophical ideas shifted

01:24:24.320 --> 01:24:30.560
[Guest]: over time. The key event, he says, is the Protestant Reformation that kind of happened,

01:24:30.560 --> 01:24:37.680
[Guest]: which changed the nature of religious practice in some of these societies. And that, I mean,

01:24:37.680 --> 01:24:44.480
[Guest]: there's a very interesting, it's a long and very detailed account. And the way people construct

01:24:44.480 --> 01:24:48.880
[Guest]: meaning, so to speak, I mean, the unstated assumptions and presumptions that shape our kind

01:24:48.880 --> 01:24:54.320
[Guest]: of understanding, which is he calls a social imaginary, has changed that. And the way he defines

01:24:54.320 --> 01:25:00.880
[Guest]: secular age is basically an age where belief and non-belief are both options for you to exercise.

01:25:00.880 --> 01:25:05.920
[Guest]: In India, I think for most people, that's not true as of now. For some people, it is true,

01:25:05.920 --> 01:25:09.840
[Guest]: like people like you and me are actually living in a secular age, so to speak, you know, because

01:25:09.840 --> 01:25:17.040
[Guest]: non-belief is very much an option. We know, we have friends who live without faith and live fairly,

01:25:17.040 --> 01:25:21.600
[Guest]: I mean, at least from the distance looks like reasonably good lives. I mean, it's not,

01:25:22.240 --> 01:25:26.320
[Guest]: seems like they are lacking anything substantial or faith is not even a factor for them,

01:25:26.320 --> 01:25:31.200
[Guest]: for some of them. But for a vast majority, I don't think that is yet the case. Because

01:25:31.920 --> 01:25:40.400
[Guest]: when they still are embedded in the social and kind of cosmic kind of systems in which

01:25:40.400 --> 01:25:45.760
[Guest]: their imaginary is placed, and there is variation of that. So, it's not every person who practices

01:25:45.760 --> 01:25:50.560
[Guest]: religion practices the same way. Right? There are a lot of variations of the way people

01:25:50.560 --> 01:25:56.560
[Guest]: practice religion in India. But some people prefer this experiential mode of you know,

01:25:57.360 --> 01:26:02.960
[Guest]: they give more importance to meditation and all of those kind of things. And some are much more

01:26:03.920 --> 01:26:08.480
[Guest]: in the bhakti mode and much more of the entanglement with the deity and kind of,

01:26:08.480 --> 01:26:12.720
[Guest]: you know, that is what important some are much more infused with narratives

01:26:12.720 --> 01:26:18.320
[Guest]: of historical identity much more. Some are much more doctrinal, they actually so most of us are

01:26:18.320 --> 01:26:22.560
[Guest]: just hearing the Vedas, they actually understand what's in there, you know, what are most of us

01:26:22.560 --> 01:26:30.160
[Guest]: just sound. So, there are different variations, but how do you go from there to a society where

01:26:30.160 --> 01:26:34.640
[Guest]: it's just an alternative and then you can shift, you know, we can be ups and downs and all of that.

01:26:34.640 --> 01:26:38.800
[Guest]: But for many, many communities in India, it's not such an obvious option, you know, it's not

01:26:38.800 --> 01:26:44.480
[Guest]: that you just move to non belief and you can still find a lot of order like if you go to my

01:26:44.480 --> 01:26:49.040
[Guest]: village, I have my host of a family lives in my village. It's just religion orders your life in

01:26:49.040 --> 01:26:53.920
[Guest]: many ways, you know, the whole year is ordered around events that are actually in some ways,

01:26:54.480 --> 01:26:59.040
[Guest]: a part of the religious calendar, so to speak, social and religious are the same, so to speak.

01:26:59.920 --> 01:27:05.040
[Guest]: And your own life is also ordered, there is this sanskar that you go through all of that. So,

01:27:05.040 --> 01:27:10.080
[Guest]: then to just move away from that into a different kind of life is not such an obvious option,

01:27:10.080 --> 01:27:13.680
[Guest]: it may happen over time. And it may happen very rapidly also, who knows, you know,

01:27:13.680 --> 01:27:17.440
[Guest]: urbanization is happening, many things are happening, and forming transformations are

01:27:17.440 --> 01:27:24.640
[Guest]: happening. So, if you go to a Swadhyay movement, meeting in say rural Gujarat that I have attended

01:27:24.640 --> 01:27:32.240
[Guest]: earlier years ago, they are much more interested in discussing, talking about the Gita and

01:27:32.240 --> 01:27:37.600
[Guest]: discussing the message of Gita and all of that. They take religion very differently from say the

01:27:37.600 --> 01:27:43.200
[Guest]: art of living, you know, which is much more of a self-help type of kind of transformation

01:27:43.200 --> 01:27:46.880
[Guest]: of religion. How this transformation will transform the way religion looks in India is

01:27:46.880 --> 01:27:50.960
[Guest]: very different, very, very difficult to say. And these are the things, the questions worth

01:27:50.960 --> 01:27:55.600
[Amit Varma]: studying and understanding as we go. So, I have a bunch of follow-up questions,

01:27:55.600 --> 01:28:02.000
[Amit Varma]: but before that an aside, I wrote a column a few years ago about how I was once at a dinner

01:28:02.000 --> 01:28:06.480
[Amit Varma]: with my friends, and there were seven of us at the table and at one point it struck us

01:28:06.480 --> 01:28:10.800
[Amit Varma]: that all of us were non-believers. And we were asking each other the question, okay,

01:28:10.800 --> 01:28:15.280
[Amit Varma]: when did you first realize that you were an atheist? And what you just said is absolutely

01:28:15.280 --> 01:28:20.560
[Amit Varma]: true that that is like a remarkably unusual thing for India that those of us who are non-believers,

01:28:20.560 --> 01:28:23.920
[Guest]: by which I mean me. Let me ask you two questions. Do you believe in God?

01:28:24.960 --> 01:28:28.000
[Guest]: No. Do you believe in socialism?

01:28:28.000 --> 01:28:32.960
[Guest]: No. So, you are in 0.01%. The no to these two

01:28:32.960 --> 01:28:36.000
[Amit Varma]: questions put you in a very, very small minority in India.

01:28:36.000 --> 01:28:39.440
[Amit Varma]: I already did tell you that there are three and a half libertarians in India. So,

01:28:40.080 --> 01:28:47.440
[Amit Varma]: if you add that to the mix, it's like, yeah, there's very little. So, I have a bunch of

01:28:47.440 --> 01:28:54.160
[Amit Varma]: questions and one is just again, I'm thinking aloud and wondering that, you know, the economist

01:28:54.160 --> 01:28:59.040
[Amit Varma]: Steven Landsberg, who wrote the famous book, the armchair economist, I think, but he also

01:28:59.040 --> 01:29:03.280
[Amit Varma]: wrote a book called Big Questions in which he made an interesting point about religion and

01:29:03.280 --> 01:29:09.760
[Amit Varma]: belief in God, where he basically said that, if you look at revealed preferences, most people who

01:29:09.760 --> 01:29:14.960
[Amit Varma]: profess to believe in God don't really believe in God because they would not put their faith in God

01:29:14.960 --> 01:29:19.760
[Amit Varma]: if it came to the crunch in a life and death situation. And the thought that kind of strikes

01:29:19.760 --> 01:29:27.840
[Amit Varma]: me when we talk about people being religion, to what extent is religion just a happenstance peg

01:29:27.840 --> 01:29:33.040
[Amit Varma]: along which they place their tribal allegiances, that is everybody wants to belong, you want to

01:29:33.040 --> 01:29:38.160
[Amit Varma]: belong to a community of people and have that sense of belonging and this is my home and these

01:29:38.160 --> 01:29:46.000
[Amit Varma]: are my people. And to what extent is religion merely a peg for that, not involving true

01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:49.280
[Amit Varma]: religious belief and again, I'm thinking aloud and not…

01:29:49.280 --> 01:29:53.760
[Guest]: I think the assumption in Landsberg's argument, which is, I think it's a flawed assumption that

01:29:53.760 --> 01:29:59.680
[Guest]: there is some kind of a comprehensiveness to religiosity that once you say you're religious,

01:29:59.680 --> 01:30:05.280
[Guest]: everything you do should be based on that and should be informed on that. But I think it's

01:30:05.280 --> 01:30:11.200
[Guest]: much more interesting the way we, you know, the modes of knowledge that we kind of use.

01:30:11.200 --> 01:30:16.080
[Guest]: So, I can recommend another book to you, this Paul Wain who is a teacher at the College of

01:30:16.080 --> 01:30:20.480
[Guest]: France has this book called, Did the Greeks Believe in Their Myths? You know, in which he

01:30:20.480 --> 01:30:27.280
[Guest]: tries to show how different modes of knowledge and imagination shape different aspects of our

01:30:27.280 --> 01:30:33.040
[Guest]: lives. And these contradictions, which from outside look like contradictions for the person

01:30:33.040 --> 01:30:37.600
[Guest]: who is holding this, what is called the constitutive imagination are actually not

01:30:37.600 --> 01:30:42.800
[Guest]: contradictions. They are just different modes in which you operate. So, he gives an example of a

01:30:42.800 --> 01:30:47.840
[Guest]: Coptic Christian in Ethiopia, who believes that the leopard is Christian and therefore will not

01:30:47.840 --> 01:30:54.640
[Guest]: eat meat during Lent, but he still keeps his cattle protected during Lent. So, he believes that,

01:30:54.640 --> 01:30:59.600
[Guest]: but he also, so one of it is this religious truth that he believes in, his experience of having

01:31:00.480 --> 01:31:04.960
[Guest]: leopards eating or killing them. So, there are different modes and they both operate

01:31:04.960 --> 01:31:11.360
[Guest]: differently in life. Human beings are not this kind of internally consistent, single value

01:31:11.360 --> 01:31:16.000
[Guest]: beings. So, there we often have contradictions that we, which appear to be contradictions from

01:31:16.000 --> 01:31:21.680
[Guest]: outside, but there is a certain amount of coherence that one feels. The feeling of life is

01:31:21.680 --> 01:31:27.520
[Guest]: very different from its perception from the outside. So, and anybody who claims that there

01:31:27.520 --> 01:31:32.000
[Guest]: is a perfect consistency over everything they do, I mean, if you look closely, you will find that

01:31:32.000 --> 01:31:37.520
[Guest]: there is a lot of like, Wittgenstein used to say that, if you want to figure out if somebody is

01:31:37.520 --> 01:31:43.440
[Guest]: religious, don't ask them, observe them. So, sometimes people actually without knowing do

01:31:43.440 --> 01:31:47.440
[Guest]: things that are quite religious. But your point would be that it doesn't necessarily mean that

01:31:47.440 --> 01:31:50.320
[Amit Varma]: they're not religious or they don't really believe, it's just that there are different

01:31:50.320 --> 01:31:55.200
[Amit Varma]: aspects to one's personality. So, for example, the same way it is completely reasonable for a

01:31:55.200 --> 01:32:00.000
[Amit Varma]: scientist to believe in God, or for a person who is rational in other ways to say go to a homeopath.

01:32:00.000 --> 01:32:05.200
[Guest]: So, we are operating in a different mode of existence. So, and we do believe have a very

01:32:05.760 --> 01:32:09.760
[Guest]: interesting and complex existence. Like one of my favorite writers, C.S. Lewis,

01:32:10.960 --> 01:32:15.520
[Guest]: he has this great quote in one of his books that, if there are desires in me that nothing in this

01:32:15.520 --> 01:32:20.800
[Guest]: world can satisfy, the only logical conclusion is that I was made for another world. You know,

01:32:20.800 --> 01:32:24.880
[Guest]: so there are aspects of our being that are not satisfied by running the human genome project,

01:32:24.880 --> 01:32:26.640
[Amit Varma]: for example. Which is a teleological statement,

01:32:26.640 --> 01:32:32.160
[Guest]: just saying I was made for another world. So, like, you're not satisfied by those things,

01:32:32.160 --> 01:32:38.320
[Guest]: and then you seek other ways to satisfy them. And religion is one part of it. For some people,

01:32:38.320 --> 01:32:43.200
[Guest]: it's everything. A great deal of their life is shaped by religious beliefs. And quite a few

01:32:43.200 --> 01:32:47.520
[Guest]: religious thinkers say that everything, for example, in Christianity, this idea of the Holy

01:32:47.520 --> 01:32:53.600
[Guest]: Spirit, in whose presence you do all your acts in Catholic, is that everything you do should

01:32:53.600 --> 01:32:59.040
[Guest]: be sacred and everything should be towards the teleology that a Catholic thought has.

01:32:59.040 --> 01:33:03.200
[Amit Varma]: But India's favorite Holy Spirit is old monk, sorry, carry on.

01:33:04.320 --> 01:33:07.840
[Guest]: Okay, that's really everything. Taking conversation to a

01:33:07.840 --> 01:33:08.560
[Guest]: blasphemous level.

01:33:10.800 --> 01:33:16.720
[Guest]: But so I think it's a, I'm not saying that all contradictions are good, and we should all kind

01:33:16.720 --> 01:33:20.960
[Guest]: of celebrate contradictions necessarily. But all conditions are not bad. I mean,

01:33:20.960 --> 01:33:24.960
[Guest]: this is not a simple thing. I mean, people can see different things in different modes of our

01:33:24.960 --> 01:33:30.160
[Guest]: life. We don't, for example, in a family situation with our family, we're not playing the same,

01:33:30.160 --> 01:33:35.840
[Guest]: I mean, role that we do elsewhere. And we are not, we don't approach situations in the same

01:33:35.840 --> 01:33:39.760
[Amit Varma]: way we do elsewhere. Now, I don't even think it's necessarily a bad thing, because people

01:33:39.760 --> 01:33:42.960
[Amit Varma]: contain multitudes. And that's something we should celebrate, because that's what

01:33:43.520 --> 01:33:48.160
[Amit Varma]: being human is all about. But but to cut to sort of another question now, like earlier,

01:33:48.160 --> 01:33:52.800
[Amit Varma]: you use the phrase, shifting from being a religious society in the context of how the

01:33:52.800 --> 01:33:56.960
[Amit Varma]: West has kind of managed that and parts of the West, parts of the West are managed that and we

01:33:56.960 --> 01:34:01.440
[Amit Varma]: are still very religious. So two questions. One is such a shift desirable in the sense,

01:34:01.440 --> 01:34:05.840
[Amit Varma]: is it something to aspire to as a society or as individuals within a society? And number two,

01:34:06.640 --> 01:34:10.560
[Amit Varma]: do you see the shift becoming possible in India at a future point in time?

01:34:10.560 --> 01:34:16.240
[Guest]: So the first question I cannot answer because it's I don't know what is the

01:34:16.240 --> 01:34:21.040
[Guest]: frame in which I would answer that question whether decline of religion will be necessarily

01:34:21.040 --> 01:34:24.640
[Guest]: a good thing or a bad thing, because I don't know what it will take, what will take its shape.

01:34:24.640 --> 01:34:26.640
[Guest]: It could be replaced by some other belief system or narrative.

01:34:26.640 --> 01:34:33.600
[Guest]: What it will be replaced by. There are parts of, for example, the explanations of why World War

01:34:33.600 --> 01:34:38.560
[Guest]: Two happened and the Holocaust happened, which go into this question about decline of religion

01:34:38.560 --> 01:34:45.280
[Guest]: led to this gap in which Nazis and other fascism and different ideologies, even communism,

01:34:45.280 --> 01:34:50.880
[Guest]: could take their place and the worst monster of 20th century, people like Stalin, Hitler and

01:34:50.880 --> 01:34:55.120
[Guest]: Pol Pot are non-religious and they could take this place. And so there are these, I don't know

01:34:55.120 --> 01:34:59.840
[Guest]: whether there's much validity to this account, but there are very serious people who have made

01:34:59.840 --> 01:35:04.880
[Guest]: these kind of accounts. So it's possible that religions may decline and something very bad

01:35:04.880 --> 01:35:11.440
[Guest]: could take their place. It is also possible that religion may continue and may actually,

01:35:11.440 --> 01:35:17.200
[Guest]: that may not be a good thing because it may take a form that we don't, that doesn't lead to the

01:35:17.200 --> 01:35:20.720
[Guest]: outcomes that are good. But because it's ultimately a question of counterfactual, right?

01:35:20.720 --> 01:35:27.600
[Guest]: Like what could exist? We can't really answer that. We participate in this world with very

01:35:27.600 --> 01:35:34.000
[Guest]: limited knowledge and on a very specific situation, we are able to bring all our worldviews

01:35:34.000 --> 01:35:39.280
[Guest]: and say, take a, with great difficulty take a view. How do I then answer this big question about

01:35:39.280 --> 01:35:45.040
[Guest]: whether decline religion will be a good or a bad thing? I can't, I mean, we can just hope that

01:35:45.040 --> 01:35:50.640
[Guest]: whatever happens will be good and we should try to make the best out of it. On the second question,

01:35:50.640 --> 01:35:56.400
[Guest]: this is interesting because as you know, and we discussed earlier that religiosity has increased

01:35:56.400 --> 01:36:01.200
[Guest]: in India, at least in some areas. Is it a problem? Is increasing religiosity in India a problem?

01:36:02.240 --> 01:36:07.840
[Guest]: No, I don't think it's a problem in and of itself. Okay. It could become a problem. It could become

01:36:07.840 --> 01:36:13.520
[Guest]: a problem in some ways. It could become a problem if it's just religiosity is used in a way that

01:36:14.400 --> 01:36:17.920
[Guest]: leads to problems for some communities and all of that.

01:36:17.920 --> 01:36:21.600
[Amit Varma]: Because some would argue that over the last five years, what you've gradually seen is increasing

01:36:21.600 --> 01:36:28.480
[Amit Varma]: polarization, attacks on minorities, lynchings, all of those things. So, some would argue that

01:36:28.480 --> 01:36:34.560
[Amit Varma]: the expression of the increased religiosity in India is a problem in our politics. Some would

01:36:34.560 --> 01:36:42.400
[Guest]: argue. These are, so, I want to say that these things that you just mentioned, lynching and all

01:36:42.400 --> 01:36:46.720
[Guest]: are nothing to do with religion. I mean, people, some people are motivated by religion to do these

01:36:46.720 --> 01:36:52.320
[Guest]: things. But this is not a central tendency of the religious people. It's not central to what

01:36:52.320 --> 01:36:57.280
[Guest]: an average religious person stands for. So, there are potentialities within the religious

01:36:58.080 --> 01:37:03.440
[Guest]: worldview or world views that can lead to such things also. And there are potentialities that

01:37:03.440 --> 01:37:10.560
[Guest]: lead to great acts and deeds. So, I mean, Mahatma Gandhi was deeply influenced by religious thought.

01:37:10.560 --> 01:37:17.040
[Guest]: I mean, the idea of incisive, the core of Jain thought. So, he was inspired. So, there are many

01:37:17.040 --> 01:37:20.720
[Guest]: good things that have come out of it. So, we can't talk about these things in a deterministic way.

01:37:20.720 --> 01:37:24.720
[Guest]: That's what I'm trying to say that if religion rises, it can lead to good things also,

01:37:24.720 --> 01:37:29.360
[Guest]: because religions have the potential to lead to greatness and goodness and all of that.

01:37:29.360 --> 01:37:30.800
[Amit Varma]: Philanthropy, serving others.

01:37:30.800 --> 01:37:35.200
[Guest]: Yeah, not just philanthropy also, just better human beings also, you know,

01:37:35.200 --> 01:37:40.960
[Guest]: like better communities, better human beings. And through that, many, many changes and

01:37:40.960 --> 01:37:46.560
[Guest]: the best way to change is through, if one person gets better, because he is inspired to get better,

01:37:47.120 --> 01:37:52.880
[Guest]: then that's significant, right? And then it can go in that direction or it could go in another

01:37:52.880 --> 01:38:00.080
[Guest]: direction. So, I can't take this one phenomenon and make a deterministic prediction that it might

01:38:00.080 --> 01:38:01.280
[Guest]: be good or bad.

01:38:01.280 --> 01:38:08.560
[Amit Varma]: But is it fair to argue that then it's perfectly reasonable to say that religiosity is compatible

01:38:08.560 --> 01:38:13.520
[Amit Varma]: with the Nehruvian socialist idea of India? Or I won't say socialist, the Nehruvian secular idea

01:38:13.520 --> 01:38:14.080
[Amit Varma]: of India?

01:38:14.960 --> 01:38:22.000
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, modes of religiosity are. So, for example, I would say that the Nehruvian idea

01:38:22.640 --> 01:38:27.440
[Guest]: and Ambedkar's ideas were not consistent with the mode of religiosity that says that

01:38:27.440 --> 01:38:32.400
[Guest]: certain castes can't enter certain temples. So, those are not consistent. That's one mode

01:38:32.400 --> 01:38:36.720
[Guest]: of religiosity. Other modes of religiosity are perfectly, I mean, nobody is saying that

01:38:37.280 --> 01:38:43.200
[Guest]: you can't seek the kind of enlightenment that average Hindu is supposed to seek or

01:38:43.200 --> 01:38:48.880
[Guest]: can't participate in social communities, which are shared religious denomination,

01:38:48.880 --> 01:38:55.680
[Guest]: or you can't read the doctrines of Hindu religion, or you can't identify yourself in terms of

01:38:55.680 --> 01:38:59.920
[Guest]: the narratives of Hindu identity that goes back or Muslim identity or Christian identity as the

01:38:59.920 --> 01:39:05.520
[Guest]: case may be, or you can't do other aspects of most of religion is for you to practice,

01:39:06.160 --> 01:39:12.480
[Guest]: even if that interventionist state is doing its bit to kind of look at the use of state power to

01:39:12.480 --> 01:39:16.160
[Guest]: reform the religion, even then a lot of it is still available to you.

01:39:16.800 --> 01:39:25.520
[Amit Varma]: So, let's kind of come to one issue where religion, or at least the excuse of religion

01:39:25.520 --> 01:39:32.160
[Amit Varma]: has become a big part of politics, which is a whole Ayodhya issue, which, of course, has been

01:39:32.160 --> 01:39:37.120
[Amit Varma]: festering from, you know, it's like I read this fascinating book, which was recommended to me,

01:39:37.120 --> 01:39:41.680
[Amit Varma]: in fact, by Akar Patel and I'll link it from the show notes. I think it's called Ayodhya,

01:39:41.680 --> 01:39:48.560
[Unknown]: the Dark Knight, but NIGST by two co authors named Jha, in which, which is a fascinating

01:39:48.560 --> 01:39:55.200
[Amit Varma]: account of how in the late 40s and early 50s, you had the Hindu Mahasabha, which is just coming out

01:39:55.200 --> 01:40:01.200
[Amit Varma]: of the ban after Gandhi's death, trying to figure out how to make its political space and deciding

01:40:01.200 --> 01:40:06.720
[Amit Varma]: that one issue that will help them mark out a space for itself will be by contesting Ayodhya,

01:40:07.280 --> 01:40:12.480
[Amit Varma]: the mosque. And then there is this whole thing where they organize this event and they have a

01:40:12.480 --> 01:40:18.480
[Amit Varma]: group of people who go sneak in in the dead of night and they plant an idol of Lord Ram in the

01:40:18.480 --> 01:40:24.240
[Amit Varma]: mosque in Ayodhya. And the issue festers from then on until the current year is very interesting,

01:40:24.240 --> 01:40:28.240
[Amit Varma]: because then you realize that a lot of the Congress were in a sense sympathetic towards

01:40:28.240 --> 01:40:33.440
[Amit Varma]: these forces, including the Chief Minister, I think it was Govind Ballapant at that time,

01:40:33.440 --> 01:40:40.400
[Amit Varma]: who was a protege of Sardar Patel. And one of the people who was inactive and did nothing at that

01:40:40.400 --> 01:40:45.200
[Amit Varma]: time to stop this happening was Lal Bahadur Shastri, who was Home Minister of UP. Despite,

01:40:45.200 --> 01:40:50.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, Nehru's furious missives to all of these people saying do something, this can't go on,

01:40:50.080 --> 01:40:54.720
[Amit Varma]: solve this issue and none of them really bothered, which makes Nehru seem like, you know,

01:40:54.720 --> 01:41:00.640
[Amit Varma]: a statesman who's all on his own and the currents in the party are against him. But then Sardar

01:41:00.640 --> 01:41:06.480
[Amit Varma]: Patel dies and Nehru establish himself as completely in charge. But that whole Ayodhya

01:41:06.480 --> 01:41:11.680
[Amit Varma]: issue, sort of you could say, in a sense was born out of a political compulsion for a party to

01:41:11.680 --> 01:41:18.240
[Amit Varma]: establish its USP and positioning, you know, and got new life perhaps in the early 90s, late 80s,

01:41:18.240 --> 01:41:23.760
[Amit Varma]: early 90s for that very reason when the BJP which got I think only about three or four seats in the

01:41:23.760 --> 01:41:33.040
[Amit Varma]: 84 elections needed to sort of find a way to get back into public consciousness and use the Ayodhya

01:41:33.040 --> 01:41:39.440
[Amit Varma]: issue. So how much of that issue is politics, how much of it is religion and and it's still

01:41:39.440 --> 01:41:46.720
[Guest]: festering what's going to happen? I mean, how do you know what like, for one person, it may be

01:41:46.720 --> 01:41:50.720
[Guest]: actually about religion, it is faith and for another person, it may be an opportunity

01:41:51.680 --> 01:41:58.240
[Guest]: to mobilize and all that. But one interesting thing is that this such kind of continuity of

01:41:58.240 --> 01:42:03.040
[Guest]: these issues, right, for example, we talked earlier about Karapatri Maharaj, he was one of

01:42:03.040 --> 01:42:08.960
[Guest]: those people who were instrumental, he started the Ram Rajya Parshad and all, which started these

01:42:08.960 --> 01:42:15.680
[Guest]: issues in some ways, very one of the initial kind of mobilizers around this issue of Ayodhya,

01:42:15.680 --> 01:42:23.760
[Guest]: Kashi, Mathura, then this issue of I mean, Hindu code, basically the uniform civil code,

01:42:24.320 --> 01:42:30.480
[Guest]: which became that issue later. This is the issue of inclusion of tribals into the Hindu kind of

01:42:30.480 --> 01:42:35.920
[Guest]: fold. So you take their practices and apply Hindu metaphysics to that and say you're Hindus.

01:42:35.920 --> 01:42:40.800
[Guest]: So these issues have kind of been the same for such a long time, right? There is such persistence

01:42:40.800 --> 01:42:49.120
[Guest]: to them is quite remarkable, I think, because it's been a small number of issues have been the

01:42:49.120 --> 01:42:55.360
[Guest]: center of mobilization for a very long time, almost 50-60 years now, longer than that. So

01:42:56.080 --> 01:43:01.440
[Guest]: there is a, in Ayodhya, the issue is of course, because it's one of those things that all over

01:43:01.440 --> 01:43:05.600
[Guest]: the world you see that place of religious significance, a conflict around that is very

01:43:05.600 --> 01:43:11.040
[Guest]: difficult to resolve. There is a mosque, which is a place of religious significance.

01:43:11.840 --> 01:43:15.040
[Guest]: Some people argue that, hey, it's not so important, it was just another mosque,

01:43:15.040 --> 01:43:20.320
[Guest]: it's not so central as it is to Hindus, who because it's a place where Lord Ram was born.

01:43:20.320 --> 01:43:25.440
[Guest]: So it is much more important to them. But as you know, in religions, the importance and

01:43:25.440 --> 01:43:30.240
[Guest]: of a particular spot is only people who practice that religion can say so it's very difficult to

01:43:30.240 --> 01:43:34.320
[Guest]: actually for somebody from outside that, you know, say that, hey, you give up this land or

01:43:34.320 --> 01:43:38.800
[Guest]: somebody else to say that is not so important for you, it depends on them. So, therefore,

01:43:38.800 --> 01:43:43.840
[Guest]: there is a really difficult situation if it were some other kind of property dispute,

01:43:44.640 --> 01:43:50.160
[Guest]: then it would have been much easier to resolve. So, if you were to just wear your constitutional

01:43:50.160 --> 01:43:54.400
[Guest]: lens, you would say that this is a property dispute, you just look at the property rights

01:43:55.440 --> 01:44:00.640
[Guest]: and settle them. That's one way but it seems that the Allahabad High Court and also now the

01:44:00.640 --> 01:44:05.120
[Guest]: Supreme Court has said that that way is not going to work. I don't know why they did that,

01:44:05.120 --> 01:44:10.000
[Guest]: because it is possible that they just look at that and then let the chips fall where they may,

01:44:10.000 --> 01:44:15.120
[Guest]: who knows where it's going to go, but they have decided to not wear that hat and they want to

01:44:15.120 --> 01:44:20.800
[Guest]: find some conciliation. But conciliation is very hard on these issues because it's not so much

01:44:20.800 --> 01:44:28.080
[Guest]: just about that particular spot. It's there is a larger politics around it, right? Like,

01:44:28.080 --> 01:44:34.320
[Guest]: you can make compromises, but sometimes the compromises may lead to consequences which are

01:44:34.320 --> 01:44:40.480
[Guest]: not acceptable to you. Now, what are the, see, and even if it leads to consequences that are

01:44:40.480 --> 01:44:44.240
[Guest]: not acceptable to you, you still have to make compromises, you know, because compromise is

01:44:44.240 --> 01:44:49.680
[Guest]: good for politics, right? Because it leads to peace and it can lead to harmony, you know,

01:44:49.680 --> 01:44:57.840
[Guest]: if there is conflict, you can diffuse it, you can find opportunity to find, to promote peace

01:44:57.840 --> 01:45:04.080
[Guest]: in society and fraternity can grow and all of that. But there is also a counter view that if

01:45:04.080 --> 01:45:11.200
[Guest]: you compromise, you might be accentuating certain tendencies, which may go further. So, this is the,

01:45:11.200 --> 01:45:18.720
[Guest]: you know, argument about a slippery slope that where is this going to go. So, one risk, for

01:45:18.720 --> 01:45:27.200
[Guest]: example, from the point of view of say, the Muslim community, so to speak, is that there is the

01:45:27.200 --> 01:45:34.560
[Guest]: chance that this might, if they compromise on this, they can be a larger, you know, mobilization

01:45:34.560 --> 01:45:40.240
[Guest]: around such issues, and it might change the nature of the Indian state, you know. And if

01:45:40.240 --> 01:45:45.520
[Guest]: there is some confidence building that or some measures that build trust to say that that is not

01:45:45.520 --> 01:45:50.240
[Guest]: going to happen, then you could find compromise around the issue. So, it's not so much about that

01:45:50.240 --> 01:45:54.720
[Guest]: particular spot that is, I mean, that there is something to that, of course, it's a sacred spot.

01:45:54.720 --> 01:46:00.400
[Guest]: But also what the larger politics of religion around that, and what kind of regime will it

01:46:00.400 --> 01:46:06.480
[Guest]: lead to? I mean, if such compromises are made, does it lead to a better regime or a worse regime

01:46:06.480 --> 01:46:10.240
[Guest]: from the point of view of a specific community and also for the point of view of common good

01:46:10.240 --> 01:46:16.000
[Guest]: for all of us? That's the important question. And that question is a political question. That's a

01:46:16.000 --> 01:46:21.600
[Guest]: question that has to be answered by all of us and also people who are involved in mobilizing

01:46:21.600 --> 01:46:27.840
[Guest]: around it to create this trust that this is not going to lead to further, you know, and it's not

01:46:27.840 --> 01:46:34.480
[Guest]: going to lead to domination by one side or the other. And I don't know whether that is happening

01:46:34.480 --> 01:46:35.040
[Guest]: enough.

01:46:35.040 --> 01:46:41.520
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, what would you say, just sort of looking at this uneasy ongoing interplay between

01:46:41.520 --> 01:46:47.120
[Amit Varma]: religion, society and the state? What would you say is like a best case scenario and a worst case

01:46:47.120 --> 01:46:49.280
[Amit Varma]: scenario over the coming 10 years?

01:46:49.280 --> 01:46:54.400
[Guest]: The best case scenario, I mean, in general, in an abstract way, but looking also at Indian

01:46:54.400 --> 01:47:04.240
[Guest]: society is that religion plays a role for creating, I mean, ethical, good human beings

01:47:04.240 --> 01:47:10.960
[Guest]: over time helps play that role, you know, but plays a role in that process. Virtuous citizens,

01:47:10.960 --> 01:47:11.680
[Guest]: so to speak.

01:47:11.680 --> 01:47:14.000
[Amit Varma]: Turning barbarians into virtuous citizens.

01:47:14.000 --> 01:47:22.240
[Guest]: That's true. And they then participate in a democratic process through this kind of

01:47:23.040 --> 01:47:29.920
[Guest]: virtuous stance and then the other ideological contestations can happen in a better way

01:47:29.920 --> 01:47:34.720
[Guest]: over time because of this. And all religions can do that, they have the potential to do that.

01:47:36.960 --> 01:47:43.280
[Guest]: Even though right now, every, some religions may in their practice look certain way, others look a

01:47:43.280 --> 01:47:47.280
[Guest]: little better, but every religion has the potential to do that, at least the major

01:47:47.280 --> 01:47:53.920
[Guest]: religions that we have in our subcontinent. And that's the, I mean, so this religious

01:47:53.920 --> 01:47:58.160
[Guest]: associations or the forms of associations, creating, helping create these kind of

01:47:59.360 --> 01:48:04.800
[Guest]: citizens who are, who care for the good. They may disagree on what is the good, but they think

01:48:04.800 --> 01:48:11.120
[Guest]: about it, care about it and serious, are serious about it and think about the common good, think

01:48:11.120 --> 01:48:19.600
[Guest]: about a good society and participate in that spirit. Also, certain amount of toleration,

01:48:19.600 --> 01:48:25.600
[Guest]: you know, of the other, of the other points of view can come also through your religious

01:48:26.320 --> 01:48:31.120
[Guest]: interactions with other people of different religions and all that. That also is good for

01:48:31.120 --> 01:48:35.760
[Guest]: society. That's good for democracy because democracy is about differences, negotiating

01:48:35.760 --> 01:48:40.720
[Guest]: those differences, that practice you can get in your religious thinking and all that.

01:48:40.720 --> 01:48:45.760
[Guest]: So, I'm just thinking about various ways in which a positive good outcome can come.

01:48:45.760 --> 01:48:47.280
[Amit Varma]: That's the best case. What's the worst case?

01:48:48.160 --> 01:48:53.840
[Guest]: The worst case scenario, I think in terms of, I mean, where we are right now is this,

01:48:53.840 --> 01:48:59.520
[Guest]: what we talked about earlier, a war of groups against groups, you know, where it's just a

01:49:00.480 --> 01:49:06.000
[Guest]: Schmittian construct, but more of, you know, group sense that you think that that community

01:49:06.000 --> 01:49:13.200
[Guest]: is your enemy and they'll destroy you if you don't do anything and you do a lot of projection,

01:49:13.200 --> 01:49:18.000
[Guest]: you know, as a psychologist, you project a lot of negativity onto them, which may not be actually

01:49:18.000 --> 01:49:22.640
[Guest]: belonging to them. They may be much more, much more boring than the demons that you describe

01:49:22.640 --> 01:49:29.280
[Guest]: them to be, but you project onto them, then it becomes a war of community against community.

01:49:29.280 --> 01:49:37.840
[Guest]: And that I think is a disaster for our democracy because I don't see, we don't have the, I mean,

01:49:38.800 --> 01:49:44.720
[Guest]: we don't have resources to overcome that because it is not so obvious that we have any,

01:49:46.000 --> 01:49:52.000
[Guest]: you know, sources of order that we can go to, which once this process starts playing out,

01:49:52.000 --> 01:49:57.600
[Guest]: which can then intervene and kind of make things better before a lot of harm is done.

01:49:57.600 --> 01:50:02.160
[Guest]: So, it has to be prevented much more than anything. And that prevention is not just

01:50:02.160 --> 01:50:08.160
[Guest]: about political, you know, coalition building, that is part of it, you have to build coalitions,

01:50:08.160 --> 01:50:14.000
[Guest]: you have to figure out ways to, it's also a culture and much more about finding a new symbol

01:50:14.000 --> 01:50:21.360
[Guest]: for community, through which we can kind of associate and overcome the centuries of resentment

01:50:21.360 --> 01:50:28.080
[Guest]: and, you know, there's a truth to this resentment that we have. There's been a lot of, I mean,

01:50:28.080 --> 01:50:33.680
[Guest]: like Ambedkar's book on partition, where he makes a list of riots and this and that,

01:50:34.400 --> 01:50:39.200
[Guest]: and other activities, other things that we can keep thinking about and keep becoming

01:50:40.080 --> 01:50:44.560
[Guest]: slaves to, you know, the past is the worst kind of tyranny because you can't change it.

01:50:44.560 --> 01:50:52.560
[Guest]: So, there is a sense of becoming a victim to, I mean, prisoners of our past, we need to find a new

01:50:53.200 --> 01:50:59.200
[Guest]: symbol to overcome that. It's not an intellectual or analytical exercise, it cannot be willed into

01:50:59.200 --> 01:51:04.160
[Guest]: existence, we can just hope and pray that it comes about. Because if it doesn't come about,

01:51:05.360 --> 01:51:09.600
[Guest]: I mean, the worst case scenario can also happen, because we are a Bajjri cultural society,

01:51:09.600 --> 01:51:13.040
[Guest]: we have different, very, very different worldviews, we can agree on many things,

01:51:13.040 --> 01:51:18.000
[Guest]: we have a constitutional project, which we are trying to implement for the last 70 years.

01:51:18.000 --> 01:51:23.680
[Guest]: That is one kind of at least an intellectual set of ideas around which quite a few of us can kind

01:51:23.680 --> 01:51:28.160
[Guest]: of get together more or less, we may disagree on the specifics of it. But it's much more of a

01:51:28.160 --> 01:51:33.840
[Guest]: cultural question about what is a symbol around which we can say that, okay, this symbol can help

01:51:33.840 --> 01:51:41.840
[Guest]: us transcend this baggage that we carry in our psyche. We have been carrying it for a long time,

01:51:41.840 --> 01:51:49.200
[Guest]: and we keep reminded of it all the time. And how long can this kind of go on. But I would argue

01:51:49.200 --> 01:51:53.840
[Guest]: that I mean, I may be sounding like a doomsayer, because we are able to find order, right?

01:51:54.400 --> 01:51:57.440
[Guest]: Sometimes intellectuals think, oh, my God, things are going to be weird, but people are able to

01:51:57.440 --> 01:52:02.080
[Amit Varma]: still find ways to live together. Amid all that despair, there is a note of hope. So let me sort

01:52:02.080 --> 01:52:06.880
[Amit Varma]: of end the episode by assuring my listeners that even though I'm one of the three and a half

01:52:06.880 --> 01:52:11.840
[Amit Varma]: libertarians in this country, and I probably disagree with all of you, I don't think of the

01:52:11.840 --> 01:52:17.280
